{If carried out under optimal circumstances, the "Dutch attack" based on ...
Ne4 and ...f7-f5 can be very dangerous, even against strongest opponents.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 d6 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. e3
b6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Ne4 11. Qc2 f5 12. b4 Rf6 {A typical way to start the
attack, based on White's slight delay in development.} 13. d5 {The typical
answer.} ({White does not have time to expel the central knight with} 13. Ne1 {
, as after} Rh6 14. f3 $2 Qh4 {Black's attack is decisive.} 15. fxe4 Qxh2+ 16.
Kf2 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 fxe4 {, followed by ...Qh2+ and ...Rf6+ or ...Rf8+.}) 13...
Rg6 (13... Rh6 {is a worthy alternative.}) ({After having temporarily spoiled
his coordination with the last move, Black should decline the pawn sacrifice:} 
13... exd5 $6 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Bb2 Rg6 16. Rad1 $16 {, with a very strong
initiative in the centre.}) 14. Bb2 (14. dxe6 {is comfortably met with} Nf8 15.
Bb2 Nxe6 $11) 14... c5 $5 {Another move to remember. Black intends to deprive
White's minor pieces of the d4-square while creating the positional threat ...
exd5, with a favourable Benoni structure.} (14... e5 {is also playable, but
White can get some relief with} 15. Nd2) 15. dxc6 (15. dxe6 Nf8 {leaves White
with problems activating his knight. Probably best is} 16. Ne1 {, aiming to
solve this problem with Nd3-f4, but then Black's attack is sufficient to force
a quick draw:} Qh4 17. e7 Ne6 18. f3 Rh6 19. fxe4 Qxh2+ 20. Kf2 Qh4+ {With the
squares f6 and f8 controlled by White, Black only has a perpetual. White must
agree to a draw, as if} 21. g3 $2 Qh2+ 22. Ng2 Bxe4 {wins.}) 15... Bxc6 16.
Rad1 Qe7 17. g3 e5 {We have now transposed to the second structure mentioned
above. Black has a weakness on d5 and a backward pawn on d6, but White cannot
take advantage of any of these. The knight is far away from d5 while the pawn
on d6 is safely defended by the attacking rook. Moreover, the bishop on b2 is
passive and as difficult it may be to believe that, it is not easy for White
to find a constructive plan. Against neutral white play, Black can increase
his kingside pressure with moves such as ...Rf8, ...h5-h4, possibly combined
with ...N g5.} 18. Nd2 $2 {This gives Black free hands for his attack.} Qh4 {
Threatening ...Nxg3, but also ...Nxd2 followed by ...Qxh2.} 19. Bf3 Qh3 20.
Rfe1 Rh6 21. Nf1 {Sadly, the knight will never reach d5 in this game.} Nxg3 $1
22. fxg3 (22. Bxc6 Nxf1 23. Bg2 Rg6 24. f4 Nxe3 $19) 22... Bxf3 $19 {Black has
won a pawn and increased his positional advantage.} 23. Rd2 Qg4 24. Qb3 Kh8 25.
Rf2 Rc8 26. c5 bxc5 27. Qf7 Nf6 28. Qe6 Rg8 29. Qxd6 Ne4 30. Qxe5 Ng5 0-1

