{In the previous game, the weaknesses induced by g2-g3 eventually turned
decisive. But Black's kingside initiative works even against a more harmonious
white structure.} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 b6 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. Nf3 Bb4 5. Qc2 f5 6. a3 Bxc3+
7. Qxc3 Nf6 8. e3 O-O 9. b3 Qe7 10. Bb2 d6 11. Be2 Ne4 12. Qc2 Nd7 13. O-O Rae8
{Black has developed harmoniously, delaying a direct attack and keeping the
possibility of ...e6-e5.} 14. Ne1 e5 15. f3 Ng5 16. d5 {White has eliminated
the risk of an early attack, but Black remains well regrouped and now only
needs to activate his bishop.} c6 17. dxc6 {The standard reaction.} (17. e4 {
turns the e4-pawn into a target.} fxe4 18. fxe4 Nf6 19. Bd3 Ng4 {, with an
initiative.}) (17. Rd1 cxd5 18. cxd5 {leaves White with worries about d5.} Rc8
19. Qd2 Nf7 {, followed by ...Nf6, with harmonious play.}) 17... Bxc6 18. Rd1
Nc5 19. Qc3 {It appears that White does not have a clear plan yet.} (19. Nd3 {
runs into} e4 $1 {This is an idea to always keep in mind. If for any reason
White cannot react with f2-f4, ...e5-e4 is an excellent way to increase the
bishop's activity.} 20. Nxc5 exf3 21. Bxf3 Qxe3+ $17) (19. b4 $2 Ba4 $17 {
loses the exchange.}) 19... Rf6 20. Bc1 {Still preparing b3-b4 and taking
measures against ...f5-f4, once the knight will reach e6.} Rg6 {This is more
of a psychological trick, inducing the next move. But in fact Black does not
threaten much yet.} (20... Rh6 {was just as good.}) 21. Kh1 $6 {The king is
more exposed on the h-file. But White has a hard time generating counterplay,
anyway.} (21. b4 Nce6 22. Qd3 Rd8 $15 23. Qxf5 $2 e4 {traps the queen.}) (21.
Qb2 Nce6 $15) 21... Rh6 $19 {Suddenly White has no defence.} 22. b4 ({This
allows a decisive combination, but removing the queen from the exposed square
does not reduce the strength of Black's attack:} 22. Qb2 Qf7 23. Rf2 ({Or if} 
23. f4 exf4 24. exf4 Nge4 25. Kg1 Nc3 $19 {, with a horrendous initiative.})
23... Qh5 24. g3 e4 25. f4 Nf3 $19 {, with a decisive attack.}) 22... Nge4 $1
23. fxe4 Nxe4 24. Qb2 Qh4 {A strong practical move.} ({But Black could
continue his combination with} 24... Ng3+ $1 25. Kg1 Rxh2 $1 {Threatening ...
Qh4.} 26. Kxh2 Qh4+ 27. Kg1 Qh1+ 28. Kf2 Ne4+ 29. Kf3 Qh5+ {, mating next.})
25. Nf3 Ng3+ 26. Kg1 Bxf3 27. Bxf3 Qxh2+ 28. Kf2 e4 29. Be2 f4 30. Ke1 Qxg2 $6
{[%cal Gh6h2] This throws away part of Black's advantage.} (30... Nxf1 31. Bxf1
Rf6 $19 {would have continued the attack with at least material equality.}) 31.
Rf2 $2 ({Missing his chance with} 31. c5 $1 {White clears the f1-a6 diagonal
for his bishop, threatening Bc4+ on the way. Black would not have anything
better than} Qxe2+ 32. Qxe2 Nxe2 33. Kxe2 f3+ 34. Ke1 bxc5 35. bxc5 Rc8 $1 {
, with just the better ending, for instance} 36. cxd6 Rc2 37. Rd4 (37. Bd2 Rxd6
$19 {leaves White paralyzed.}) 37... Rxc1+ 38. Kf2 Rc2+ 39. Kg3 Rf6 {
Threatening ...Rg2+, with a mating attack.} 40. Rg1 Rc8 $17 {Black is better,
but the win is far from obvious yet.}) 31... Rh1+ 32. Bf1 Rxf1+ 33. Rxf1 Qxf1+
34. Kd2 Qe2+ 0-1

