{The sequence d4-d5, ...c7-c6 can also happen without a previous kingside
expansion. Even though in such cases the kingside attack is not such a
critical issue, Black retains adequate play with careful planning.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 b6 7. e3 Bb7 8. b4 d6 9.
Bb2 Nbd7 10. Be2 Qe7 11. O-O e5 {To tell the truth, I have considered using
this plan for our repertoire. But I was worried about Black's chances of
counterplay if White maintains the tension.} 12. d5 {This makes it simpler for
Black.} (12. Qc2 {, clearing the d2-square for the knight in case of ...e5-e4,
is more consistent.}) 12... Rfd8 13. Qc2 c6 14. dxc6 Bxc6 15. Rfd1 Rac8 16. Qb3
Qe6 {Both sides have completed their development and Black retains a solid
position. Both sides' plans in the next phase are rather slow. In principle,
Black should keep his central pawns on the dark squares and set up some
kingside pressure. But after everything has been done properly, ...d6-d5 and ..
.b6-b5 may be an effective way to exploit the relative weakness of White's
queenside light squares.} 17. Nd2 {The knight was not doing much on f3. Now it
defends the queen, preventing an early ...b6-b5.} Nf8 {The knight is heading
for g6 while also clearing the d-file, in order to over-defend Black's
backward pawn.} 18. f3 h5 {The simple advance of the h-pawn will soon create
certain discomfort on White's kingside.} 19. Bf1 h4 20. a4 {At this height,
the only active plan. It is amusing that the culmination of the manoeuvring
phase will be reached when both rook pawns will be on their fifth rank.} (20.
h3 {consolidates the light squares but weakens g3, allowing} Nh5) 20... Ng6 21.
a5 d5 {Black cannot improve his piece placement anymore, so he decides that
the time has come for a pawn break. But inserting either ...h4-h3 or ...e5-e4
before the central break strongly is also an option:} (21... h3 {weakens the
pawn on f3.} 22. g3 d5 {Let us compare this to the line in which White plays
as in the game} 23. axb6 axb6 24. b5 dxc4 25. Qxc4 {White has to keep f3
defended.} (25. Bxc4 Bd5 $17 {leaves White chronically weak on the light
squares.}) 25... Qxc4 26. Nxc4 (26. Bxc4 Bxf3 $1 27. Bxf7+ Kxf7 28. Nxf3 Rxd1+
29. Rxd1 Rc2 30. Rd2 Rxd2 31. Nxd2 Ke6 {It is White already who has to think
of a safe way to equality.}) 26... Rxd1 27. Rxd1 Bxb5 28. Nxe5 (28. Nd6 Rc2 $11
) (28. Nxb6 $2 Rb8 $19 {loses a piece.}) 28... Nxe5 29. Bxe5 Bxf1 30. Kxf1 Rc2
$11) (21... e4 {forces White to weaken the g4-square.} 22. f4 d5 23. axb6 axb6
24. b5 Bb7 25. Ra7 dxc4 26. Nxc4 (26. Bxc4 Bd5 $19 {, with a chronic weakness
on d3.}) 26... Bd5 {Threatening ...Ng4 but also ...h4-h3.} 27. h3 Ne7 {,
followed by ...Nf5, with great play for Black.}) 22. axb6 axb6 23. b5 dxc4 (
23... Bb7 24. Ra7 dxc4 25. Nxc4 Rxd1 26. Qxd1 Bd5 {is also playable, but the
rook on a7 is a bit annoying.}) 24. Nxc4 $6 ({If} 24. Qxc4 Bd5 25. Qb4 Nd7 {
, followed by ...Nc5, with good stability for Black. And still, this would
have been a better choice for White.}) 24... Rxd1 25. Qxd1 ({A necessary pawn
sacrifice, as if} 25. Rxd1 Bd5 26. Rc1 h3 {, White has problems keeping his
light squares together.}) 25... Bxb5 26. Nd6 Rd8 27. Bxb5 Qxd6 28. Qb3 $2 {
Allowing Black to attack with the queens on the board is hardly a good idea.} (
28. Qxd6 Rxd6 {was better, even though Black has great play anyway. The extra
pawn is not so relevant at this stage, but the threat ...Rd2 followed by ...
h4-h3 is annoying. For instance} 29. Bc3 Nd5 30. Rd1 (30. Bd2 Nc7 31. Bb4 Nxb5
32. Bxd6 Nxd6 {is a better version of the main variation for Black.}) 30...
Nxc3 31. Rxd6 Nxb5 32. Rxb6 Nc3 {Black's winning chances are questionable, but
he can play on, of course.}) 28... h3 29. Be2 (29. g3 {allows} Nh4 $1 30. gxh4
Ne4 $19) 29... Qd2 30. Kf2 (30. Bf1 hxg2 31. Bxg2 Nh4 32. Bh1 Qe2 $19 {,
threatening ...Rd2.}) 30... Rd6 31. Ra8+ Kh7 32. gxh3 Ne4+ $1 33. Kf1 (33. fxe4
Rf6+ {wins.}) 33... Rf6 34. Qd1 Rxf3+ $1 35. Kg1 Qxe3+ {An impressive attack
after a laborious manoeuvring phase.} 0-1

