{The other plan for White after getting the two bishops is based on g2-g3.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2
a5 9. b3 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 {Even though Black has developed in absolutely the
same way as after 7.e3, the slightly different circumstances induce a change
of plan. The familiar ...Ne4 followed by ... f7-f5 is less effective. First of
all, Black does not have chances for a kingside attack and secondly, the
knight may fall under a pin after Ng5. But at the same time, by developing his
bishop to g2, White has weakened the defence of the queenside light squares.
While ...e6-e5 remains a reasonable reserve or complementary plan, Black
should logically prepare a queenside counterattack based on ...b6-b5 (with or
without ...a5-a4). White can prevent it with a3-a4, but in this case Black can
switch to ...e6-e5 after some preparation, yielding him absolute control over
c5.} *

