1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. Bg2 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 Be4 8.
Qd1 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 a5 13. a3 {A curious
opening move order has led to one of our main tabiyas, with the difference
that it is Black to move! While it is true that play usually develops slowly
at this stage and the tempo is not of the highest relevance, it is certainly
useful. I would like to mention that the bishop is optimally placed on e4, as
it prevents the idea d4-d5 while also restricting the white queen and blocking
the advance of the e-pawn. At the same time, Black has to always take Bh3 (or
Rfe1 and Bf1) into consideration, followed by a knight move and f2-f3, e2-e4.}
Qb8 {Immediately switching to the main plan.} 14. Qf4 ({If} 14. a4 {, the most
principled idea is to return with the queen to the kingside:} Qe8 {Planning ...
e6-e5, possibly after ...Rad8.} 15. Bh3 Bb7 {With the bishop on h3, ...e6-e5
makes less sense. The bishop retreat prepares against White's obvious plan.}
16. Ne1 Ne4 17. Qe3 h6 $5 {Allowing the knight's retreat to g5 after f2-f3.}
18. Nd3 ({Or if} 18. Bg2 f5 19. Nd3 c5 $5 {Reaching a favourable version of a
familiar structure after the pawn exchange, since Black will have the
c5-square.}) 18... Ng5 19. Bg2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 f5 $11 {Possibly followed by ...
Nf7 and ...e6-e5.}) 14... Qb7 15. Rfe1 {A constructive move that also sets a
small trap.} b5 $1 ({It is worth mentioning that here inserting} 15... a4 $6
16. b4 {before} b5 {does not work so well, as after} 17. cxb5 Qxb5 {White has}
18. Bf1 {unblocking the centre soon.}) 16. c5 {The most consistent move, even
though it concedes control over d5. White was not prepared against the threats
...bxc4 or ...a5-a4, ruining his queenside.} ({The difference is that after} 
16. cxb5 Qxb5 {the pawn on b3 is hanging.} 17. Nd2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 a4 {Now is a
good moment to fight for more control over the light squares.} 19. b4 Nd5 20.
Qe4 f5 $1 $11 {, with great play. The pawn on e6 is not tasty:} 21. Qxe6+ $2
Kh8 {, and the queen is trapped.} 22. e4 N7b6 $1 23. exd5 Rae8 $17) 16... Qd5 {
Taking the offered square and attacking both b3 and c5.} ({If} 16... dxc5 $6
17. dxc5 $14 {, the pawn is taboo due to Bxf6.}) 17. Qe3 {A correct decision.
White prefers to sacrifice a pawn rather than release the tension.} ({If} 17.
cxd6 $6 cxd6 18. Qe3 Nb6 {, followed by ...a5-a4, Black's domination on the
light squares would be crushing.}) 17... Rfb8 $6 {Since Black will not play ...
b5-b4, this is a strange move.} ({In fact, the c5-pawn was not really poisoned:
} 17... dxc5 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Qxc5 Nxc5 20. Nd4 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Nfd7 {and White
has just normal compensation due to his more harmonious pieces.}) ({But I
would prefer} 17... b4 18. a4 {White should keep the queenside closed.} Rad8 {
The threat ...dxc5 becomes real after Black completed his development.} 19.
Rac1 {A natural move, which deprives the queen of the c1-square, though.} Ng4
$1 20. Qf4 f5 {Defending the bishop and threatening ...Qxb3.} 21. Rc4 h6 22.
Qc1 Rf7 {, and Black's kingside attacking chances may become real.}) 18. Rac1
h6 {Preparing the following manoeuvre.} 19. h3 Qf5 20. Nh4 Qh7 21. f3 Bd5 22.
Bf1 {Black is about to lose control in the centre.} a4 $6 {A rather simplistic
solution.} ({Black should have made use of the relative weakness of White's
kingside with} 22... Nh5 23. Kh2 (23. g4 Ng3 $11 {exchanges the f1-bishop, as
if} 24. Bg2 g5 {traps the knight.}) 23... g5 24. Ng2 b4 25. a4 f5 {, with
mutual chances.}) 23. b4 Bc4 24. Qf2 d5 25. Ng2 Re8 26. g4 $14 {Black has
managed to consolidate on the light squares, but White has more space and
enjoys the more flexible structure. (0-1 after 87 moves).} 0-1

