{Finally, we should examine a few typical aspects of the position with central
tension, arising when Black plays ...d6-d5 and ...c7-c5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 d6 8. Be2 a5 9. b3 Nbd7 10.
Bb2 O-O 11. O-O Qe7 12. Rad1 Rfd8 13. Qc3 {This is one of our repertoire
tabyias, but I have chosen a game which was not included in the theoretical
database.} Qf8 $5 {A subtle move, over-defending g7 and thus preparing ...
c7-c5. In principle, it corresponds with Black's philosophy in this line. He
maintains his flexibility for as long as possible, staying ready to
counterattack in the centre in response to White's play.} ({Our repertoire
line goes} 13... d5) (13... c5 $6 {is premature due to} 14. d5) 14. Ne1 {
Since Black did not play ...Ne4, the regrouping initiated by this move is not
very natural.} (14. Nd2 c5 15. Rc1 {, followed by Rfd1, is more harmonious.
The main idea is that after ...d6-d5xc4 White has Nxc4, putting certain
pressure on the black queenside.}) 14... c5 15. Nc2 {Obviously not a great
square for the knight.} ({But if} 15. Nd3 {, the pawn on c4 is likely to
become vulnerable.} cxd4 16. Qxd4 (16. exd4 Rac8 {, followed by ...Ba6 and ...
d6-d5, is also comfortable for Black.}) 16... Rac8 {We have reached a familiar
structure where White's unnatural regrouping leaves his queenside a bit
vulnerable.}) 15... d5 {Since White's pieces are massed in the centre without
a clear idea, now is a good moment to challenge him in that area.} 16. a4 {
White consolidates his pawn on c4 by preventing ...a5-a4 and clears the
knight's path to b5. But on the other hand, his last move ensures Black
stability on c5.} (16. f3 {is met with} a4 {, when White cannot maintain
control over the light squares, for instance} 17. b4 cxb4 18. Qxb4 Rdc8) ({
Or if} 16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. f3 cxd4 18. Nxd4 e5 19. Nf5 Rac8 20. Qd3 Be6 {, and
White is hanging a bit.}) 16... Ne4 17. Qe1 dxc4 {This may be a bit premature.}
({Since the rook did not have much to do on a8 anymore, completing development
with} 17... Rac8 {may be better.} 18. Bd3 Nd6 19. Na3 Bc6 20. Bc2 {Defending
a4 in order to answer ...dxc4 with bxc4.} cxd4 21. exd4 Nf6 22. Qe2 (22. Nb5 $2
{loses a pawn to} Bxb5 {, as the bishop is hanging on c2.} 23. axb5 dxc4 $17 {
In this line we notice an aspect mentioned in the theoretical database: Black
compensates for the potentially strong bishop on b2 by a more harmonious
regrouping. White should have his rooks on c1 and d1, but for concrete reasons
that is not easy to achieve at an early stage.}) 22... Nf5 {With active play.})
18. bxc4 (18. Bxc4 {allows} Nd6 $11) 18... Bc6 19. Ra1 Rac8 20. f3 Nef6 21. Qg3
Qe7 $5 {The queen returns to e7 with the same purpose for which it had
retreated to f8: Neutralise the pressure on g7 by enabling ...Nf8-g6.} 22. Rfe1
Nf8 23. Bf1 Ng6 24. dxc5 bxc5 25. Bc3 Ra8 {The structure is symmetrical now,
but the familiar knight regrouping ensures Black counterplay despite the
strong bishop on c3.} 26. Reb1 Nd7 27. Ra2 ({Now was the only moment when
White had a chance for active play:} 27. Na3 $1 {Finally solving the problem
of the passive knight.} Bxa4 28. Nb5 Bxb5 29. Rxb5 a4 30. Ba5 Re8 ({The more
natural} 30... Rdc8 {has the drawback that after} 31. Rxa4 Nh4 32. Bc3 Nf5 {
the rook is hanging, allowing} 33. Rxa8 $1 Rxa8 34. Qf2 {, with the more
pleasant position for White.}) 31. Rxa4 Nh4 32. Qe1 Nf5 33. Rb7 Nd6 34. Rb3 {
For the time being, White is pinned, but if he manages to retrieve his
coordination, his position will be more pleasant due to the two bishops.})
27... h5 $1 {Once again a familiar idea. The threat ...h5-h4-h3 is not easy to
meet.} 28. Qe1 $6 {White does not find a better idea than attacking a5, but
the pawn on f3 is vulnerable now.} (28. h3 {weakens the square g3 and can be
answered with} h4 29. Qf2 Nf6 {, followed by ...Nh5.}) (28. Qf2 {is a more
harmonious regrouping, but} h4 {, followed by ...Qg5 and the advance of the e-
and f-pawns, offers Black adequate play anyway.}) 28... Nde5 $1 {Threatening
not only ...Nd3 but also ...Bxf3.} 29. Rb6 $2 {Just a blunder. Radjabov
thought that his last move parries both threats but overlooked an intermediate
move.} (29. Qf2 {was better, but Black's position is very pleasant after} Nd3
30. Bxd3 Rxd3 {anyway.}) 29... Bxf3 $1 30. Bxe5 Nxe5 31. Qg3 Nd7 $1 {Probably
overlooked by White.} 32. Rbb2 Be4 {At this stage Black is completely winning.
But it is worth following the next phase, probably played in time trouble, as
there are a few tactical moments.} 33. Na3 Nf6 34. Ra1 Bf5 35. Nb5 Ne4 36. Qe5
Rd7 37. Be2 Qg5 38. Qf4 Qf6 39. Rba2 Qg6 40. h3 Rad8 41. Qh4 Rd2 42. Nd4 $5 {
A desperate try.} R8xd4 $2 {This yields Black only good compensation for the
exchange.} (42... Bxh3 $1 {would have won by force.} 43. Qxh3 ({If} 43. Bf3 Ng5
$1 44. Bxh5 Rxa2 45. Bxg6 Rxg2+ 46. Kh1 cxd4 {Black has a strong attack and a
material advantage.}) 43... Rxa2 $1 {With the queen away from h4, the rook on
d8 is not hanging anymore.} 44. Rxa2 cxd4 $19) (42... Rd7 $17 {was also good.})
43. exd4 Rxd4 44. Qxh5 Qxh5 45. Bxh5 Rxc4 46. Be2 Rc3 (46... Rd4 $11) 47. Rb2
c4 48. Rb8+ Kh7 49. Rc8 Nd2 50. Ra2 $2 {Leaving the back rank undefended.} Rc1+
51. Kf2 c3 (51... Ne4+ $1 52. Ke3 Rc3+ 53. Kd4 f6 $1 {Threatening to win the
rook with ...e6-e5.} 54. Rxc4 (54. Rc6 e5+ 55. Kd5 Rc1 {leaves the king out of
play and exposed.}) 54... e5+ 55. Kd5 Rxc4 56. Bxc4 (56. Kxc4 Be6+) 56... Nc3+
57. Kc5 Nxa2 58. Bxa2 Bd3 {, and Black should convert his extra pawn as White
cannot go for the a5-pawn:} 59. Kb6 e4 $19) 52. Ke3 {The position remains
unclear and I assume that Black lost on time.} 1-0

