1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 {This is not the most active and
desirable knight development, but it enables White to win the bishops' pair
without compromising his pawn structure, as often happens in the Nimzo-Indian.}
b6 {I feel that this is the system that corresponds best with the Bogo-Indian
spirit. Black agrees to give up the dark-squared bishop and prepares to take
control over the light squares. This is the most popular system, but by far
not the only viable one.} (4... O-O {is a bit too provocative for my taste.} 5.
a3 Be7 6. e4 d5 (6... d6 {is also popular, but I feel that Black is playing
some kind of inferior King's Indian.}) 7. e5 Nfd7 {White's centre is likely to
become vulnerable after ...c7-c5, but he has certain kingside attacking
chances.}) ({I am not too thrilled by} 4... c5 5. a3 {, either. Black gives up
the bishop and opens the centre, hoping that his slight lead in development
and the weakness on b3 will offer him counterplay. But play becomes too
concrete at an early stage for my taste.}) ({I have successfully experimented
with} 4... d5 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. a3 Be7 {, but justifying the knight's placement
in front of the c-pawn is not easy.}) 5. a3 {The most principled continuation.}
({For} 5. e3 {, see Lines 15-16.}) (5. g3 {is examined in Lines 17-18.}) 5...
Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 {This looks like the most logical continuation: One should
develop the minor pieces first and only later the queen. But after giving up
the possibility of Bb2, the bishop will face some problems staying active.} ({
The important alternative is examined in Lines 8-14.} 6. Qxd2) 6... Bb7 7. Bf4
{Not a very popular move, as the bishop's pressure along the h2-b8 diagonal is
relatively easy to neutralise.} (7. b4 {is part of White's general plan, but
played at this stage it looks like a potential waste of time.} Ne4 8. e3 O-O 9.
Be2 f5 10. h4 $6 ({White does not have any kingside attacking chances, and he
has just wasted another tempo to weaken h4 and g4. But after the relatively
better} 10. O-O {, apart from transposing to the main variation in Line 2,
Black can use the tempo to exchange the bishop under more comfortable
circumstances than in a sideline mentioned there:} Nxd2 11. Nxd2 d6) 10... d6
11. a4 Nd7 12. a5 Rb8 13. Qc2 Ndf6 14. axb6 axb6 15. Ra7 Ng4 16. O-O {Joksic,S
(2335)-Barbero,G (2440) Biel 1998 (0-1, 58)} Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Bxf3 $17 {wins the
pawn on h4:} 18. gxf3 $2 Nh2 $1 $19) (7. e3 {is the subject of Line 2.}) ({For
} 7. g3 {see Line 3.}) (7. Bg5 {will be dealt with in Lines 4-7.}) 7... d6 8.
e3 Nbd7 9. Be2 ({The seemingly more active} 9. Bd3 {exposes the bishop to ...
e6-e5-e4 after} Qe7) 9... Qe7 10. h3 {A typical way of ensuring the bishop's
retreat in all kind of openings with Bf4.} (10. O-O {leaves the bishop exposed.
} e5 11. dxe5 (11. Bg5 {is just a waste of time.} h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. dxe5
dxe5 14. Qa4+ Qd7 15. Qc2 Qe6 16. c5 O-O 17. Rac1 Bd5 $11 {Levin,E (2483)
-Karasev,V (2361) St Petersburg 2010 (1/2-1/2, 45)}) (11. Bg3 $146 Ne4 {
does not change much compared to the mainline.}) 11... dxe5 12. Bg5 (12. Bg3
Ne4 $11) 12... h6 13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 O-O-O {Due to the bishop's exposure,
Black's pawn attack sustained by the b7-bishop is likely to develop at least
as fast as White's, Eriksson,M (1823) -Brasoy,A (2011) Tromsoe 2010 (1-0, 38)})
10... Ne4 {Now that the bishop has a safe retreat square, Black switches to
the Queen's Indian Dutch setup.} 11. Bh2 {White should continue regrouping and
developing on the kingside.} (11. Qc2 {looks like a premature commitment, as
White's main plan is based on exchanging the e4-knight with Nd2.} a5 12. b3 (
12. Bd3 f5 13. O-O-O {, as in Farago,S (2395)-Horvath,G (2410) Hungary 1989 
(0-1, 40), exposes the king. One possible way to get attacking chances with
Black is} O-O 14. Rhg1 Rac8 15. Kb1 c5 16. Qe2 b5 $5 17. cxb5 Nb6 18. Rc1 c4 $1
19. Bxc4 Nxc4 20. Rxc4 Rxc4 21. Qxc4 Rc8 22. Qe2 Qc7 $17 {Black has an attack
with opposite-coloured bishops. White's bishop is a mere spectator while
White's attack has not even started yet.} 23. g4 $2 Qc3 $1 {The queen is taboo,
as in the end the knight on f3 is hanging.} 24. gxf5 Qb3 $19) 12... f5 (12...
g5 $5 13. Bh2 h5 14. d5 Ndc5 $11) 13. Bh2 O-O 14. O-O Rf6 {This attack is
partly possible because of the tempo wasted by White.} 15. Rfd1 Rg6 16. d5 e5 {
With at least equal chances.} 17. Nd2 $6 {Kiss,P (2380)-Horvath,G (2420)
Zalakaros 1992 (1-0, 35)} Nxd2 18. Rxd2 Nc5 19. Rdd1 Qh4 $17) (11. O-O f5 12.
Bh2 {is another possible move order.}) 11... f5 12. O-O (12. Rc1 {is a similar
waste of time as Qc2.} a5 13. b3 O-O 14. O-O Rf6 $146 (14... e5 {justifies Rc1:
} 15. c5 $1 {This works only because e5 is under tension.} bxc5 16. dxe5 dxe5
17. Bb5 $14 {Khalifman,A (2640) -Arkell,K (2450) London 1991 (0-1, 42)}) 15. d5
e5 16. Nd2 Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Rg6 18. b4 Qg5 19. Bg3 Nf6 $11) 12... O-O 13. Nd2 {
White is best advised to eliminate the active knight as soon as possible.} Nxd2
(13... Qg5 14. Bf4 Qg6 {is also playable.}) 14. Qxd2 {Cebalo,M (2515)
-Andersson,U (2605) Manila 1992 (1/2-1/2, 47)} e5 {After White has weakened
the pressure on e5, this is safe and good.} 15. dxe5 {White has to extend his
bishop's diagonal.} (15. b4 Qg5 {offers Black easy play.} 16. f3 (16. d5 f4 $5)
16... exd4 17. Qxd4 Rae8 18. Bf4 Qe7 {, followed by ...g7-g5, wins the pawn on
e3 for questionable compensation.}) 15... Nxe5 16. b4 Qg5 17. Bg3 Nd7 $5 {
Not only taking measures against c4-c5 but also redirecting the knight to
f6-e4.} 18. c5 $5 {What else?} bxc5 19. Bb5 Nf6 20. bxc5 Ne4 21. Qa2+ Kh8 22.
Bf4 Qg6 23. c6 {The only way to secure the kingside, at least temporarily.} Bc8
$11 {Black is stable and the bishop on f4 fails to impress.} *

