1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 Bb7 7. e3 {
This modest-looking move is in fact quite a sensible choice. White refrains
from immediately activating the bishop and continues developing normally. If
Black exchanges on d2, this will help White's development, and if not, the
bishop could later emerge onto the long diagonal, after a retreat to e1.} O-O
8. Bd3 {There are a couple of reasons why this is the best square for the
bishop in this line.} (8. Be2 {fails to put pressure on e4 and also exposes
the bishop in a certain scenario.} d6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Qc2 ({If} 10. b4 Ne4 11.
Be1 f5 {12. Nd2 runs into 12...Nc3-+ while} 12. Qb3 {offers Black a tempo to
start his attack with} Rf6) 10... Ne4 11. Be1 f5 12. Nd2 {Since e4 is not
under much pressure, Black can ignore the tension with} Qg5 $11 13. Bf3 $2 Nxd2
14. Bxb7 Nxf1 15. Bxa8 Nxe3 $17) 8... Ne4 9. O-O f5 ({Another possible move
order is} 9... d6 10. Be1 Nd7 11. Nd2 f5) (9... Nxd2 {is playable, too, even
though it looks like a small concession.} 10. Nxd2 (10. Qxd2 $146 Bxf3 $1 11.
gxf3 f5 12. f4 d6 13. Be2 Nd7 14. Bf3 Rb8 {Since Black's structure is more
compact, the knight is not weaker than the bishop.}) 10... f5 (10... d6 $5 11.
Be4 Bxe4 12. Nxe4 Nd7 13. Rc1 f5 14. Nc3 Nf6 $11) 11. Qe2 (11. Qc2 Qf6 12. c5
Nc6 13. b4 {Loinjak,S (2554)-De Jesus,G (2313) LSS email 2011 (1-0, 62)} Ne7 $1
$146 14. cxb6 cxb6 15. Qc7 Bd5 16. Qxd7 Nc6 17. Qd6 {White takes his queen out
of danger.} Nxd4 18. exd4 Qg5 19. Qg3 Qxd2 $11) 11... Nc6 12. Rac1 Qf6 (12...
e5 $5 13. d5 e4 14. Bb1 Ne5 15. f4 exf3 16. Nxf3 Qe7 $11) 13. c5 Rae8 14. b4
Kh8 15. f4 g5 $11 {Topalov,V (2737)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2652) Tripoli 2004 (1/2-1/
2, 45)}) 10. Be1 {White not only keeps the bishop safe from the exchange but
also prepares Nd2.} (10. Qc2 Rf6 $1 11. Ne1 ({If} 11. Rad1 {, White can first
stabilize the centre and then proceed with his attack:} c5 12. b4 Rg6) 11...
Rh6 12. f4 (12. f3 Qh4 {forces White to weaken his kingside with h2-h3 , as if}
13. fxe4 $2 Qxh2+ 14. Kf2 Qh4+ 15. Ke2 Qg4+ 16. Kf2 fxe4 17. Be2 Qh4+ {, with
a winning attack.}) 12... d6 13. Nf3 Nd7 14. Ng5 Nxg5 15. fxg5 {Lenic,L (2465)
-Kuzubov,Y (2558) Kirishi 2005 (0-1, 35)} Qxg5 $1 $146 16. e4 Qf6 17. Bxh6
Qxd4+ 18. Qf2 Qxf2+ 19. Rxf2 fxe4 {, with excellent compensation for the
exchange.}) 10... d6 11. Nd2 (11. Qe2 Nd7 12. Nd2 e5 $11) 11... Nd7 {Since the
immediate attack is less promising, Black continues his development.} 12. f3 (
12. Nxe4 fxe4 13. Be2 Qg5 14. Bg4 Rf6 $11 {, with good counterplay.}) (12. Qc2
{wastes a tempo:} Nxd2 13. Bxd2 Qh4 14. f3 Rf6 15. Be1 (15. Rf2 a5 16. b3 $146
Qh5 17. Raf1 Rh6 18. g3 Rf6 {After provoking the weakening of White's light
squares, the rook returns to the centre.} 19. Bc3 Rf7 20. e4 f4 {, with
interesting counterplay.}) 15... Qh6 16. Qe2 e5 17. Bc3 Re8 18. Bc2 Qh5 19. Ba4
{Huss,A (2355)-Razuvaev,Y (2560) Bern 1998 (1/2-1/2, 18)} exd4 $3 20. Bxd4 (20.
Bxd7 Rxe3 21. Qd2 Rh6 22. h3 Re7 23. Qxd4 Rxd7 $17) 20... Rf7 21. Rae1 Re6 22.
b4 c5 23. Bc3 Qh4 {Black's centre is secure and his kingside play looks quite
promising.}) 12... Nxd2 (12... Qg5 $6 {does not seem to work properly:} 13.
fxe4 Qxe3+ 14. Bf2 Qxd3 15. Rc1 {The queen will soon be trapped.} fxe4 16. Rc3
Rxf2 17. Rxd3 Rxf1+ 18. Nxf1 exd3 19. Qxd3 Re8 20. b4 $14) 13. Bxd2 (13. Qxd2
e5 {does not make much of a difference.}) 13... e5 {The opening phase is over
and both sides have achieved their initial aims. White has exchanged the
active knight and is ready to place the bishop on the long diagonal. But Black
has raised ambitions in the centre and created the positional threat ...e5-e4,
aiming to establish control over the light squares.} 14. d5 (14. Qc2 Qf6 15.
Bc3 Qg6 $1 $146 {Black has to keep the threat ...e5-e4 alive.} (15... Qf7 $6 {
, as in Tassone,R (2002)-Packroff,H (2000) GER email 2014 (1-0, 22), is less
active.}) 16. Be2 (16. dxe5 Nxe5 $1 17. Be2 Rae8 18. b4 Qh6 19. Qd2 Nd7 {
wins the pawn on e3 for questionable white compensation.} 20. f4 $6 Qe6 $17)
16... Rae8 17. Rae1 (17. b4 Qg5 18. Qd2 exd4 19. Bxd4 c5 $17) 17... Re7 18. b4
h5 $5 {Black is solid in the centre and threatens to weaken the enemy kingside
by advancing his h-pawn as far as possible.}) (14. b4 $146 {allows Black to
show his main idea:} e4 (14... Qh4 $6 15. Qa4 $1 Rf7 16. Bxf5 $1) 15. fxe4 Bxe4
16. Bxe4 fxe4 {Black has good play on the light squares.} 17. Qb3 (17. Rxf8+
Qxf8 18. Qb3 Qf7 19. Rf1 Nf6 20. Be1 b5 $11) 17... Qe7 18. c5+ (18. b5 Qe6 19.
Bc3 Rxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Rf8 21. Rxf8+ Kxf8 $11) 18... Kh8 19. cxd6 cxd6 $11) 14...
c6 {The fastest way to activate the bishop.} 15. dxc6 (15. e4 {offers Black
counterplay against the apparently compact centre.} cxd5 16. cxd5 fxe4 17. fxe4
Rxf1+ 18. Bxf1 Nc5 19. Qf3 Qh4 20. Re1 Rf8 21. Qg3 Qf6 22. Bc4 Ba6 23. Bxa6
Nxa6 24. b4 Nc7 25. a4 b5 26. a5 Qf7 27. h3 Ne8 $11) 15... Bxc6 16. Bc2 Qe7 17.
Bc3 Rac8 $5 $146 {Preparing ...Rf6 and taking measures against b2-b4..} (17...
Rf6 $2 18. Ba4 $1 Bb7 (18... Bxa4 $2 19. Qd5+) 19. Bxd7 Qxd7 20. Bxe5 $16) (
17... Rad8 18. b4 Kh8 (18... Rf6 19. a4 $16) (18... b5 $2 19. cxb5 Bxb5 20.
Qd5+) 19. Qd2 b5 20. cxb5 Bxb5 21. Rfd1 Nb6 22. a4 Bc4 23. b5 $16 {Fuzishawa,R
(2361)-Leite,D (2324) ICCF email 2016 (1-0, 57)}) 18. Rf2 (18. b4 b5 19. cxb5
Bxb5 20. Qd5+ Kh8 21. Qxb5 Rxc3 $11) 18... Rf6 19. Rd2 Rcf8 (19... Kh8 $5) 20.
b4 Rh6 {Black has excellent counter-attacking chances.} *

