1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 Bb7 7. g3 {
This is meant to be an improved version of the plan in Line 2. White leaves
the diagonal open for the bishop on d2 and takes measures against ...Ne4 while
also avoiding any danger for his king. But the main drawback of this plan is
that it weakens the control over several light squares, such as c4, b5 and e4.
Even though this sometimes implies a pawn sacrifice, Black's control over the
central light squares offers him excellent play.} O-O 8. Bg2 d6 (8... Ne4 $2 {
allows} 9. Ng5 $1) 9. O-O Nbd7 {Black's main plan is ...Be4 followed by ...
b6-b5, possibly sustained by ...a7-a5.} 10. b4 {The most active continuation.
The scenario remains the same after other moves.} (10. Qc2 Be4 11. Qc3 (11. Qc1
a5 $146) 11... a5 $5 $146 12. b4 Qe7 13. Be3 axb4 14. axb4 b5 $11) (10. Rc1 a5
11. Qc2 (11. b3 {Burnett,J (2117)-Titz,H (2204) Dresden 2013 (1/2-1/2, 53)} Qb8
12. Bc3 a4 13. b4 b5 $11) 11... Be4 12. Qc3 a4 {After having fixed the
queenside, Black can prepare ...e6-e5, yielding him control over c5.} 13. Rfd1
Ra7 (13... Re8 14. Bh3 Bb7 {is also possible, leaving White short of active
plans.}) 14. Qe3 Qa8 15. Bc3 Re8 16. Bh3 (16. Bf1 Bb7 17. Nd2 e5 $11) 16... Bc6
(16... b5 $5) 17. Qd3 Ne4 18. Be1 Ndf6 19. Nd2 e5 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 21. Qe3 Bc6 22.
Rc2 Be4 23. Rcc1 Bc6 24. Rc2 Be4 25. Rcc1 {1/2-1/2 Cramling,P (2515)-Panno,O 
(2520) Buenos Aires 1994}) (10. Bc3 {allows} Ne4 (10... a5 $5 11. b4 axb4 12.
axb4 b5 $11) 11. Qc2 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Qe7 13. Rfd1 f5 14. b4 Nf6 $11) (10. Bg5 {
Wasting time to exchange the bishop is hardly promising.} h6 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12.
e3 Qe7 13. Re1 c5 {In the absence of the dark-squared bishop, Black can adopt
a central strategy at no risk.} 14. b4 Rfd8 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 d5 $11 {
Bellon Lopez,J (2415)-Ulybin, M (2565) Oviedo 1993 (1/2-1/2, 34)}) 10... a5 {
Strictly speaking, this is a new move, but after White's mainline answer it
will transpose to played lines.} 11. Bc3 (11. bxa5 bxa5 {mainly weakens
White's queenside. For instance d4-d5 would concede control over c5 while
Black can think of playing ...c7-c5, fixing the weakness on c4.} 12. Bc3 (12.
a4 c5 $11) 12... Ne4 13. Bb2 f5 {White has to take ...Nb6 into account, too.})
11... axb4 12. axb4 b5 $1 {The typical pawn break.} 13. cxb5 (13. c5 Be4 14.
Qb3 Nd5 15. Bb2 f5 $5 ({This looks more ambitious than} 15... N7f6 16. Rfc1 Ne7
17. cxd6 {1/2-1/2 Delchev,A (2572) -Nisipeanu,L (2666) Andorra 2003}) 16. Rxa8
(16. Bh3 Qf6 17. Nd2 Qh6 18. Nxe4 Qxh3 19. Ng5 Qh6 20. Nf3 Qg6 $15) 16... Qxa8
17. Bh3 (17. Ra1 Qe8 18. Bf1 f4 {, with excellent counterplay.}) 17... dxc5 18.
dxc5 (18. Ra1 $2 c4) 18... Qa4 $11) 13... Nb6 14. Ra5 (14. Qb3 Bd5 $11) (14.
Qc1 Rxa1 15. Bxa1 Bd5 16. Ne1 Qd7 $15) 14... Qb8 15. Nd2 {White has to take
care of the c4-square.} (15. Ne1 $6 Bxg2 16. Nxg2 Ne4 17. Qb3 d5 18. Rfa1 Qe8
$15 {, followed by ...Nd6, retrieves the pawn, soon retaining perfect control
over the light squares.}) 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Nbd5 17. Qb3 Nxc3 {Black does
not have anything better than retrieving the pawn.} 18. Qxc3 Rxa5 19. bxa5 Qxb5
20. e4 Qe2 {More or less forcing a draw.} (20... Ra8 $5 {is also possible.} 21.
Ra1 (21. Qxc7 Qxa5 $11) 21... h5 22. Qxc7 (22. Ra2 Ra7) 22... Qb2 23. Qc1 Qxc1
24. Rxc1 Rxa5 $11) 21. Qe3 (21. Ra1 Ng4 22. Rf1 Nf6 23. Ra1 Nxe4 $5 {
Refraining from a move repetition, but it does not change the evaluation of
the position.} 24. Nxe4 Qxe4+ 25. Kg1 Ra8 26. Qxc7 Qxd4 27. Rb1 g6 28. Rb8+ Kg7
29. Rxa8 Qd1+ {, with a perpetual.}) 21... Qh5 22. Qc3 (22. Ra1 $2 Ng4 $19)
22... Qe2 23. Qe3 Qh5 24. Qc3 {1/2-1/2 Grabarczyk,M (2499)-Iordachescu,V (2562)
Panormo 2001} *

