1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 Bb7 7. Bg5 {
This is the most active continuation. By pinning the knight, White wishes to
induce the weakening moves ...h7-h6 and ...g7-g5. But, as we will see, the
bishop's exposure offers Black good counterplay.} d6 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bh4 $5 {
A paradoxical retreat. The bishop clears the g-file, which will play a part
after the planned Nd2 and Be2.} (9. Nd2 {, with the same idea, offers Black a
choice.} c5 $5 {With the white knight far from the centre, this is effective.}
({If} 9... Qe7 10. Bh4 {, Black can transpose to the mainline with 10...h6 or
else deviate with} Rg8 $5 11. f3 g5 12. Bf2 e5 13. d5 e4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. fxe4
O-O-O 16. Bd3 Nc5 $11 {Heberla,B (2556)-Short,N (2680) Warsaw 2013 (1/2-1/2,
51)}) 10. f3 (10. dxc5 dxc5 {does not pose any problems, as Black does not
have to take into account d4-d5 anymore.} 11. Qc2 Qe7 12. f3 h6 13. Bh4 O-O-O
14. Be2 g5 15. Bf2 e5 16. e4 Nh5 17. g3 Ng7 18. Qa4 Kb8 19. Nb1 Ne6 20. Nc3 Nd4
21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. cxd5 f5 $17 {Solozhenkin,E (2465)-Lesiege,A (2375) Hyeres
1992 (0-1, 33)}) 10... O-O 11. Bd3 d5 {After White has wasted some time, while
also misplacing the knight, Black can fight for the centre already.} 12. O-O {
Lakhno,K (2294)-Karpov,V (2282) Voronezh 2003 (1/2-1/2, 51)} (12. cxd5 exd5 13.
O-O Re8 14. Re1 Nf8 $11 {, followed by ...Ne6.}) 12... cxd4 $146 13. exd4 Rc8
14. Qe2 Ba6 15. b3 Nb8 16. Qe3 h6 17. Bh4 Nc6 18. Rad1 Ng4 $11) ({For} 9. Qc2 {
See Line 5.}) (9. Be2 {[%emt 0:00:06] is examined in Line 6}) ({and} 9. Bd3 {
in Line 7.}) 9... h6 {Black does not have anything better, at least from the
perspective of our repertoire against White's main plans examined in the next
lines.} ({If} 9... Qe7 {, White can switch to his main plan with} 10. Bd3 {
, when due to ...Qe7 Black's kingside play is one tempo slower.}) 10. Nd2 Qe7
11. Be2 {This is the point behind the bishop's early retreat to h4.} (11. f3 {
is best answered with the familiar} c5 (11... e5 12. Be2 g5 13. Bf2 e4 14. Qc2
O-O-O {Chirila,I (2537)-Xiong,J (2476) Philadelphia 2015 (1-0, 44)} 15. O-O-O
$14 {leaves White better regrouped.}) 12. Bd3 (12. dxc5 dxc5 13. Be2 g5 14. Bf2
O-O-O {, with attacking chances on the kingside.}) 12... O-O 13. O-O g5 $146
14. Bf2 Nh5 15. b4 (15. f4 Ng7 {, followed by ...f7-f5.}) 15... f5 16. g3 Ng7
17. Qb3 Nf6 $11 {, planning ...e6-e5, with a flexible black position.}) 11...
g5 ({After} 11... Bxg2 $2 12. Rg1 {retrieves the pawn with an advantage.}) 12.
Bf3 $1 (12. Bg3 $2 {simply loses a pawn to} Bxg2) 12... O-O-O 13. Bxb7+ (13.
Bg3 {can lead to a transposition, but can also have independent value.} e5 14.
d5 $5 {This obstructs the bishop on b7, but White's bishops are not too active
either.} (14. Bxb7+ Kxb7 15. O-O h5 16. f3 h4 17. Bf2 h3 18. g3 e4 {, with
excellent play on the light squares. Shoup,K (1679)-Hesse,O (1980) GER email
