1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 Bb7 7. Bg5 d6 8.
e3 Nbd7 9. Qc2 {White delays the kingside development to keep g2 defended and
prepare d4-d5. But there are at least two reasons why this is risky.} Qe7 10.
Rd1 h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Ne4 ({In fact, the same plan as in the next two
lines is effective, even though g2 is defended:} 12... h5 $5 13. h4 (13. c5 $5
$146 {, threatening cxd6 followed by Qc7.} bxc5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. b4 h4 16.
bxc5 hxg3 17. Bb5+ Kf8 18. fxg3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 d5 {, with at least equal play
for Black.}) 13... Ne4 $1 ({With the pawn on g2 defended,} 13... g4 {is
pointless.} 14. Ng5 $14) 14. Nxg5 Nxg3 15. fxg3 O-O-O 16. Qf2 f6 17. Nh3 Rdg8
18. Nf4 {Moiseenko,A (2657)-Zelcic,R (2514) Kusadasi 2006 (1/2-1/2, 37)} f5 $1
$146 19. Be2 Nf6 $15 {, with excellent play on the light squares and along the
g-file.}) 13. d5 {The thematic move, aiming to restrict the b7-bishop and
weaken f5. Neutral moves tend to offer Black comfortable play.} (13. Nd2 Nxg3
14. hxg3 O-O-O (14... h5 {is a bit too committal, but playable, too.} 15. b4 h4
16. gxh4 Rxh4 17. Rxh4 gxh4 18. c5 {White has a certain initiative, but Black
should be able to hold his own.} bxc5 19. dxc5 dxc5 20. Ne4 Bc6 21. Nxc5 Nxc5
22. Rc1 Bd5 23. Qxc5 Qxc5 24. Rxc5 {Krasenkow,M (2615)-Macieja,B (2465) Sopot
1997 (1/2-1/2, 43)} c6 25. f3 f5 $11 {The bishop on d5 should keep Black's
position together.}) 15. g4 (15. b4 c5 16. a4 {Principled but ineffective.} f5
17. a5 f4 $5 $15) (15. c5 {gives up a pawn for no compensation:} dxc5 16. Rc1
e5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. b4 Ne6 $17) 15... f5 $1 {It appears that White's blockade
is not that stable.} 16. gxf5 exf5 17. Qxf5 Rdf8 18. Qd3 h5 19. b4 g4 {For
just a pawn, Black has a very strong initiative. Bystrov,S (2325)
-Gaprindashvili,P ICCF corr 1997 (1/2-1/2, 61)}) (13. Bd3 f5 14. d5 Ndc5 {
Now the drawbacks of Bd3 become obvious. Black has very active minor piece
play.} 15. Nd4 O-O-O (15... exd5 $5 16. cxd5 O-O 17. b4 Nxd3+ 18. Qxd3 Rae8 19.
Ne6 Rf7 20. Rc1 c6 21. dxc6 Qxe6 22. cxb7 f4 23. f3 {The least Black can do
now is simplify to an equal ending:} fxg3 24. Qxe4 Qxe4 25. fxe4 Rxb7 $11) 16.
Bxe4 fxe4 17. Nxe6 (17. O-O exd5 18. cxd5 g4 $5 {Taking measures against f2-f3.
} 19. b4 Nd3 20. Nc6 Bxc6 21. dxc6 Kb8 22. Qc4 Ka8 {With such a knight on d3,
Black cannot be worse.}) 17... Nxe6 18. dxe6 Qxe6 19. b4 {Estremera Panos,S 
(2386) -Winants,L (2524) Dresden 2007 (0-1, 41)} Rhf8 $1 {The best way to
stabilize the position and leave the bishop on g3 passive.} 20. h4 (20. O-O h5
21. h4 Qg4 $19) (20. c5 dxc5 $17 21. bxc5 $2 Rxd1+ 22. Qxd1 Ba6 $40) 20... Rf5
$15 {White does not have an active plan and has problems finding safety for
his king.}) 13... Ndf6 14. Nd4 h5 {After having activated his knights, Black
can continue his pawn attack.} 15. f3 (15. dxe6 $2 fxe6 {opens the f-file and
the long diagonal for Black's attack.} 16. Qa4+ (16. f3 h4 17. Bf2 Nxf2 18.
Kxf2 O-O-O $19) 16... Qd7 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 18. f3 h4 19. Bf2 Nxf2 20. Kxf2 Raf8
21. h3 e5 22. Nb3 Ne4+ 23. Ke1 Ng3 24. Rg1 e4 $19 {Steingrimsson,H (2470)
-Sulava,N (2544) Differdange 2007 (0-1, 49)}) 15... h4 16. Bf2 (16. Bxh4 {
The tactics work out well for Black here:} Rxh4 17. fxe4 Nxe4 18. Nf3 Ng3 19.
Nxh4 Nxh1 20. Nf3 g4 21. Nd4 g3 $15) 16... Nxf2 17. Kxf2 g4 $1 {Black has a
very strong attack.} (17... O-O-O {is also possible, but it makes sense to
delay the moment when Black exposes his king.} 18. Nc6 Bxc6 19. dxc6 Kb8 20.
Qa4 Ka8 {Fages,J-Janosi, E LSS email 2007 (1/2-1/2, 35)}) 18. e4 (18. Be2 O-O-O
19. Nc6 Bxc6 20. dxc6 Kb8 $15) (18. h3 gxf3 19. gxf3 Nh5 $15) 18... h3 $1 $146
{The pawn chain has to be attacked at its base!} (18... g3+ $6 19. Ke1 {
is less clear, Aseev,K (2520)-Kengis,E (2465) Daugavpils 1989 (1/2-1/2, 61)})
19. gxh3 gxf3 $17 *

