Nxg3 16. fxg3 f5 17. O-O O-O-O 18. bxc5 dxc5 19. a4 g4 {, with a decisive
attack.}) 15... g4 16. bxc5 dxc5 17. Ne5 cxd4 {[%csl Gd4]} 18. exd4 g3 19. Bxg3
Nxg3 20. fxg3 Nxe5 21. dxe5 Qc5 $17 {Black is a pawn down, but has the better
structure and the safer king.}) (12. Nxg5 {loses a piece without compensation.}
h4 13. Bf4 e5 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Bf3 Qc8 $17) 12... g4 13. Ng5 (13. Nd2 Bxg2 14.
Rg1 Bb7 15. f3 {may later transpose.}) 13... Bxg2 14. Rg1 Bb7 15. f3 {This is
the idea behind Be2. But Black retains excellent play on the light squares
anyway.} Qe7 $1 (15... gxf3 $2 16. Bxf3 $16) 16. Rf1 {Putting indirect
pressure on f7.} (16. fxg4 hxg4 17. Bxg4 Nxg4 18. Qxg4 {retrieves the pawn but
leaves Black with the better structure.} Nf6 (18... f5 19. Qe2 Nf6 20. Qc2
O-O-O 21. O-O-O $17 {Razuvajeva,J (2192)-Guseva,O (2135) St Petersburg 2000 
(0-1, 39)}) 19. Qe2 Ne4 20. Nxe4 Bxe4 21. O-O-O O-O-O 22. b4 (22. Bf2 Qf6 23.
Rdf1 Qf5 24. Be1 Qh7 25. Kd2 Rhg8 $17 {Hoffman,A (2435)-Hernandez Onna,R (2435)
Alicante 1989 (0-1, 108)}) 22... Kb7 23. Kb2 {Agdestein,S (2595)-Fyllingen,R 
(2330) Drammen 1994 (1/2-1/2, 29)} f5 $17) 16... Nh7 $1 {Eliminating the
danger on f7.} (16... O-O-O {offers White certain chances.} 17. fxg4 hxg4 18.
Bxg4 Nxg4 19. Rxf7 Qxg5 20. hxg5 Rh1+ 21. Ke2 Rxd1 22. Rxd1 Rg8 (22... Rf8 $2 {
Chu,W (2349)-Firman,N (2485) Albena 2014 (1/2-1/2, 30)} 23. Rxf8+ Nxf8 24. Rg1
Ng6 25. Bxd6 cxd6 26. Rxg4 $16) 23. Re7 (23. Bh4 Rh8 24. Bg3 e5 $11) 23... Be4
24. Rxe6 Bf5 25. Re7 Rxg5 $11) 17. Nxh7 (17. f4 f6 18. Nxh7 Rxh7 $17 {is
simply bad for White.}) (17. Ne4 O-O-O $17) 17... Rxh7 18. Qa4 {White's only
constructive idea is to make castling difficult for Black.} (18. fxg4 hxg4 19.
Bxg4 O-O-O $17 {leads to a familiar structure.}) 18... f5 (18... O-O-O 19. Qxa7
e5 20. c5 {offers White certain chances, Nowak,I (2435)-Makarichev,S (2495)
Frunze 1985 (1/2-1/2, 30)}) 19. O-O-O a6 20. fxg4 (20. Kb1 gxf3 21. Bxf3 O-O-O
22. Be2 a5 23. b4 Rg7 $17 {Black's counterplay will develop faster after ...
