1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 {This slightly
paradoxical move, developing the queen in front of the bishop, is the most
consistent. White intends to develop his bishop on the long diagonal, hoping
that Black will play ...Ne4, when after Qc2 White would be a tempo up compared
to similar lines in the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. Indeed, the queen reaches c2 after
moving twice, while in the Nimzo-Indian it goes along the path c2-c3-c2.} Bb7
7. b4 {Since in the main lines below Black plays ... a7-a5 on the next move,
it makes sense to check what happens if White starts his queenside expansion
at once.} (7. g3 {is examined in Line 9.}) (7. e3 {will be the subject of
Lines 10-14.}) 7... a5 {Now is a good moment to react as White is
underdeveloped.} 8. b5 {This reduces the force of White's attack by weakening
his control over c5. After a later d4-d5 or dxe5, Black gets the square c5,
while c4-c5 is more difficult to carry out.} ({But} 8. Bb2 {turns White's
queenside into a target:} Ne4 {Now is a good moment to "lose a tempo" with
respect to the Nimzo-Indian, as White is undeveloped.} 9. Qc2 (9. Qd3 axb4 10.
axb4 Qe7 $15) (9. Qc1 Qe7 $15) 9... axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1+ 11. Bxa1 Qe7 (11... Na6
$5 12. b5 Nb4 13. Qb3 c5 14. bxc6 Nxc6 15. Qa3 Qe7 16. Bb2 Qxa3 17. Bxa3 d5 18.
cxd5 exd5 19. e3 Kd7 $17) 12. c5 (12. Qb3 Na6 13. c5 O-O 14. b5 {The only way
to anticipate ...Ra8.} Naxc5 15. dxc5 Ra8 16. Qb1 Qxc5 17. Bd4 Qa3 18. Qb2 Qxb2
19. Bxb2 Ra2 20. Bd4 d6 $19 {, with a decisive lead in development.}) 12... O-O
{Black has pleasant play on the light squares.} 13. e3 f5 (13... Bd5 $5) 14.
Be2 Ng5 15. Qd1 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nc6 18. Bc3 bxc5 19. bxc5 Qh4 20.
O-O Qe4 (20... Ne7 21. Qb7 Qe4 $11 22. Qxc7 Nd5 23. Qa5 f4 $19) 21. Qxe4 fxe4
22. f3 exf3 23. Rxf3 Ra8 24. Rf2 Ra3 25. Rc2 Kf7 $11 {Ree,H (2480) -Andersson,
U (2630) Wijk aan Zee 1984 (1/2-1/2, 37)}) 8... d6 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. e3 O-O 11.
Be2 (11. Bd3 {as in Popov,V (2578)-Lezcano Jaen,P (2407) Stockholm 2002 (1-0,
36) should be met in the same way.} Ne4 12. Qe2 f5 13. O-O Rf6 14. Ne1 (14. d5
Rh6 {If anything, Black has the c5-square to play for.}) (14. c5 Bd5 15. c6 Nf8
{, with an initiative on the kingside.}) 14... Rh6 15. g3 (15. f3 $2 Qh4 16.
fxe4 Qxh2+ 17. Kf2 fxe4 $19) 15... Ng5 16. f3 Nh3+ 17. Kh1 Qe7 18. Ng2 g5 {
, with excellent counterplay.}) 11... Ne4 12. Qc2 f5 13. O-O Rf6 14. c5 (14. d5
Rh6 15. g3 Ndc5 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. Nd4 Qg5 18. Kg2 Rf8 19. Rh1 {Van Wely, L 
(2675)-Papaioannou,I (2637) Achaia 2017 (1/2-1/2, 30)} e5 $1 $146 20. Bc1 $5
Rg6 {[%cal Gg5h4] Planning ...Qh4.} 21. h4 Qf6 22. h5 Rg4 $1 $17 {, with a
massive piece attack.}) 14... Bd5 15. cxd6 {White does not gain much by
keeping the c-file closed:} (15. Bc4 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Rh6 17. c6 Nf8 18. Rfd1 Qf6
(18... Kh8 19. Qe2 Qe7 20. Nd2 Qh4 21. Nf1 Re8 22. f3 Ng5 $11 {Korobov,A (2698)
-Nadanian,A (2380) Yerevan 2015 (0-1, 38)}) 19. Qe2 Ng6 $17 {[%cal Ga8f8,Gg6e7]
followed by ...Rf8 and ...Ne7-d5, with fantastic play.}) 15... cxd6 16. Rac1
Rg6 17. g3 {White has to take prophylactic measures.} (17. Qc7 $2 Nd2 $1 $17
18. Qxd8+ Rxd8 19. Nxd2 Rxg2+ 20. Kh1 Rxf2+ 21. e4 Bxe4+ 22. Nxe4 Rxe2 23. Nxd6
Rxb2 $19) 17... Ng5 18. Nxg5 Qxg5 19. Qc7 {This is supposed to counterbalance
Black's attack.} Qh4 20. f3 (20. Qxd7 $2 Qxh2+ $1 {mates soon}) 20... Rxg3+ 21.
hxg3 Qxg3+ 22. Kh1 Nf6 23. Qc2 $2 {In Spindelboeck,G (2270)-Danner,G (2340)
Austria 2014 (1/2-1/2, 26), Black was now satisfied with a perpetual, but he
could have won with} (23. Bd1 $1 {Black can give a perpetual or else play} Ng4
24. Rc2 Qh3+ 25. Kg1 Nxe3 26. Rff2 Nxd1 27. Rg2 g6 28. Bc1 {, with a very
complicated position. If Black can get his knight back into the game, he will
win, due to his numerous pawns for the exchange, but this is not that simple.})
23... Ng4 24. Bd1 Rf8 25. Qg2 Qh4+ 26. Kg1 Nxe3 $19 *

