1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. g3 {
We are familiar with this plan from Line 3. But after Bb2, White will have a
more harmonious setup, and Black will have to work a bit on getting control of
the light squares.} O-O (7... Bxf3 8. exf3 d5 {is an interesting alternative.
With two knights against the two bishops and slightly better development,
Black has chances to take advantage of White's weaknesses.} 9. c5 {The most
challenging answer.} (9. b3 O-O 10. Be2 Qe7 11. O-O Rd8 12. Bb2 dxc4 13. Bxc4
c5 $5 {Trying to make use of White's queenside weaknesses. But 13...Nc6
followed by .. .Rd6 is also reliable.} 14. Qe3 cxd4 15. Bxd4 Nc6 16. Bb2 Nd5
17. Qe4 Na5 18. Rac1 Nxc4 19. Rxc4 Rac8 20. Rfc1 Qd7 21. Rd1 b5 22. Rxc8 Qxc8
23. Rc1 Qd7 24. f4 Ne7 $11 {Salov,V (2665)-Nikolic,P (2655) Wijk aan Zee 1997 
(1-0, 56)}) (9. Bg2 Nc6 10. f4 Na5 $5 11. cxd5 Nb3 12. Qc3 Nxa1 13. dxe6 fxe6
14. O-O Rb8 15. b4 O-O 16. Qxa1 a5 17. b5 Nd5 $11 {With just normal
compensation for the exchange.}) 9... bxc5 10. dxc5 a5 {Taking measures
against b2-b4.} 11. Bb5+ $5 (11. c6 {weakens the pawn and wastes a tempo.} d4
12. Qg5 O-O 13. Bb5 e5 14. O-O Qd5 15. a4 Re8 16. Re1 Qxf3 17. Ra3 Qd5 18. Bf4
Nxc6 $19 {Mikhalevski,A (2485)-Manor,I (2515) Israel 1999 (0-1, 23)}) (11. b3
Qe7 12. Qc2 O-O 13. Bb2 c6 14. Rc1 {Sutkus,V (2258)-Chripko,L (2576) ICCF
email 2008 (1/2-1/2, 25)} Nfd7 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Na6 17. Qc3 e5 $15 {
Due to the better structure, the knights are stronger than the bishops.}) 11...
c6 12. Ba4 Qc7 13. O-O Nbd7 {1/2-1/2 Rajkovic,D (2480)-Drasko,M (2505) Tivat
1995} 14. b4 O-O 15. Bb2 e5 16. Bc2 {, with some chances for a tiny advantage.}
) 8. Bg2 (8. b4 {is premature as usual at this stage:} a5 9. Bb2 axb4 10. axb4
Qe7 11. c5 Nc6 12. b5 Na5 13. Qb4 Ne4 $17) 8... a5 {We will see this idea in
Lines 10-14, too. The threat ... a5-a4, freezing the queenside, forces the
next move, thus slowing down White's queenside attack a bit.} 9. b3 d6 10. O-O
Nbd7 11. Bb2 Be4 {The start of a coherent plan. Black wants to forget about
the threat d4-d5 and gets ready to prepare ...b6-b5 with, say, ...Qb8.} (11...
Qe7 $6 12. d5 $1 exd5 13. Nd4 {leaves the queen vulnerable on e7.}) (11... Re8
$5 12. Rfd1 (12. d5 exd5 13. Nd4 Ne4 $17) 12... Rb8 {Defending the bishop.} 13.
Rac1 Qe7 {is solid but less ambitious.}) 12. Rfd1 {White has tried several
other moves. As we will see from the lines below, Black's fight for the light
squares can embrace a wide variety of forms.} (12. Rfe1 Qb8 13. a4 (13. Bf1 {
Cmilyte,V (2459)-Butnorius,A (2424) Siauliai 2005 (1/2-1/2, 15)} b5 14. Ng5 Bg6
15. Bg2 d5 $5 {Black achieves excellent stability on the light squares. For
instance:} 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Rac1 a4 18. bxa4 Rxa4 $11) (13. Ne5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2
Qb7+ $15 15. f3 $2 dxe5 16. dxe5 Ng4 17. Qxd7 Ne3+ 18. Kf2 Rad8 19. Qe7 Nc2 $17
) 13... Qb7 14. Bf1 (14. Nh4 Bxg2 15. Nxg2 Rfe8 16. f3 d5 17. Red1 Rac8 18.
Rac1 h6 19. Nf4 c6 $11) 14... Bxf3 $5 {Not forced, but quite interesting.} 15.
exf3 Qxf3 16. Bg2 Qxb3 {After winning two pawns, Black has no reason to fear
losing the exchange.} 17. Rec1 (17. Bxa8 Rxa8 18. Rec1 Qf3 $15) 17... d5 18.
Rc3 Qb4 19. Ba3 Qxa4 20. Qe1 Rfe8 21. Be7 Qxa1 22. Qxa1 Rxe7 {Black has enough
material for the queen and chances are about equal in a complicated position.}
23. cxd5 exd5 24. Rxc7 a4 25. Bf1 a3 26. Bb5 g6 27. Rc2 Nf8 28. Ra2 Rea7 {
, and Black is not worse at all.}) (12. b4 Qe7 $5 $146 {A useful move before
switching to the main plan.} 13. Rfd1 (13. b5 Rfe8 14. a4 Rad8 $11 {, followed
by ...e6-e5 soon.}) 13... axb4 14. axb4 b5 15. c5 Rxa1 16. Rxa1 Nb8 17. Bf1 Nc6
18. Ne1 Bd5 $11) (12. Ne1 {Meenakshi,S (2327) -Harika,D (2478) Biel 2007 (1/
2-1/2, 25)} Bxg2 13. Nxg2 Re8 $5) 12... Qb8 13. a4 {Preventing Black's plan
but virtually weakening the c5-square (and concretely the b4-square).} (13.
Rac1 b5 14. c5 b4 15. a4 Bd5 16. Qe3 {Sakaev,K (2600)-Rashkovsky,N (2530)
Elista 1996 (1/2-1/2, 54)} Qd8 $1 $146 {After contributing to stabilising the
queenside, the queen should return to the centre.} 17. Ne1 (17. Bh3 Ne4 18. Ne1
Qg5 $11) 17... Bxg2 18. Nxg2 Nd5 19. Qd2 f5 $11) 13... Qe8 $1 $146 {Same idea
as above. The queen does not have much left to do on the queenside.} (13... Qb7
14. Rac1 Rfe8 15. Qe3 Rac8 16. Bh3 c6 17. Ba3 d5 18. Ne5 $14 {Rajkovic,D (2484)
-Ostojic,N (2428) Belgrade 2005 (1-0, 39)}) 14. Rac1 Rd8 (14... Qe7 {is also
good, as} 15. Ne5 {is not too threatening.} Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Ne4 17. Nc6 Qe8 18.
Qd3 f5 19. f3 Nef6 $11) 15. Bf1 Bb7 $5 $11 {Black is well regrouped and ready
for ...e6-e5.} *

