1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 {
This is White's most consistent system after 4.Nbd2 b6. It is based on natural
development and maintaining the balance between both wings.} a5 {As we know, a
useful intermediate move.} 8. b3 O-O 9. Be2 {This is the best square for the
bishop. It not only over-defends the knight but also avoids the potential
threat ...e5-e4.} (9. Bd3 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bb2 Re8 12. Rad1 {Saucey,M (2273)
-Wirig,A (2452) Pau 2012 (1/2-1/2, 49)} e5 13. dxe5 (13. Be2 e4 14. Ne1 a4 15.
b4 d5 {, with excellent play on the light squares.}) 13... dxe5 14. Bf5 (14.
Be2 Qe7 $11) 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qe7 16. f4 Rad8 17. Qc3 exf4 18. exf4 Nc5 $11)
9... d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bb2 Qe7 {As explained earlier, Black does not have to
hurry with ...Ne4. Instead, he displays his pieces harmoniously, maintaining
the possibility of choosing his plan in accordance with White's. As we will
see, most of White's natural continuations imply a small commitment and
against many of them, Black can switch to ...Ne4 followed by ...f7-f5 anyway.
Without having a clear plan yet, White would like to regroup with Rfd1, Rac1,
Qc2, but this is not easy to achieve without allowing Black counterplay. In
this line we will examine a few rare continuations.} 12. Rfd1 {This looks like
the logical start of the optimal regrouping, but weakening the defence of f2
allows Black to start his counterplay.} (12. Ne1 {This anticipates ...Ne4,
prepares an early f2-f3, but takes the knight away from the centre.} e5 {
With the knight on e1, the threat ...e5-e4 is a bit unpleasant.} 13. f3 {
Kovalenko, I (2667)-Deszczynski,A (2366) Warsaw 2016 (1-0, 41)} e4 14. d5 (14.
f4 {allows Black to start play on the light squares:} a4 15. b4 b5 $5 16. cxb5
Nd5 17. g4 f5 18. gxf5 $6 {Blocking the kingside would lead to static equality.
} N7b6 19. Rf2 Bc8 20. Rg2 Bxf5 $15 {Black is in complete control and the
knight is poorly placed on e1.}) 14... Nc5 15. Qc3 (15. Bd1 b5 $11) 15... b5
16. Nc2 Rfe8 17. f4 bxc4 18. Bxc4 Nd3 $11) (12. Rac1 {has the drawback of
occupying the c1-square, depriving White of the possibility of defending e3
with Qc1 or Bc1 in the line below:} Ne4 13. Qc2 (13. Qd3 {keeps e3 defended
but exposes the queen.} f5 14. Ne1 e5 15. f3 Nef6 {Threatening ...e5-e4.} 16.
Qxf5 $6 exd4 17. Bxd4 c5 $17 {Retrieving the pawn on e3 with an initiative.})
13... f5 14. d5 (14. Ne1 Qg5 {is the moment when White needs some time to
prepare f2-f3.} 15. Rd1 Rf6 16. d5 Rh6 17. g3 Rf8 {, with good kingside play.})
14... e5 15. Ne1 Rae8 16. f3 Ng5 17. b4 {Gershon,A (2471)-Cebalo,M (2553)
Baden 2000 (1/2-1/2, 47)} c6 18. h4 (18. dxc6 Bxc6 19. Qd2 Rf6 {safely defends
d6 while continuing the slow kingside attack.}) 18... Nf7 19. dxc6 Bxc6 20. b5
(20. Qxf5 Qxh4 21. b5 Ng5 $17) 20... Bb7 21. Qxf5 Nc5 22. Qh3 e4 {Black is
better regrouped and has the initiative on the light squares.} 23. f4 Bc8 24.
f5 Ne5 25. g4 h5 26. gxh5 Ned3 27. Bxd3 exd3 $44 {, with obvious compensation
for the pawns.}) (12. b4 {is examined in Line 11.}) (12. Rad1 {is the subject
of Line 12.}) (12. Qc2 {leads to Line 13.}) (12. Qc3 {, transposing to a 4.Qc2
Nimzo-Indian, is Line 14.}) 12... Ne4 13. Qc2 f5 14. d5 {Preparing to exchange
the active knight as soon as possible.} (14. b4 Rf6 15. d5 Rh6 16. Bd3 e5 17.
Bxe4 fxe4 18. Qxe4 Rf8 $15 {After ...Nf6 followed by ...Bc8 Black will be
attacking with all his pieces.}) (14. Nd2 Qh4 {This is a moment when White's
vulnerability on f2 yields Black a tempo.} 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qd2 Rf6 17. f3 Rh6
18. h3 Bb7 $11 {With enough kingside play.}) 14... e5 15. Nd2 Qh4 $5 $146 ({
I find this even more consistent than} 15... Nxd2 16. Rxd2 Qg5 17. Rf1 f4 $1 {
Preventing f2-f4 and consolidating on the dark squares.} 18. exf4 exf4 (18...
Qxf4 19. Rd3 $5 $14) 19. f3 Ne5 20. Bd3 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 Rae8 $11 {Cifka,S (2410)
-Voloshin,L (2456) Czechia 2010 (1/2-1/2, 45)}) 16. Rf1 {As a result of the
premature Rfd1, White is forced to lose two tempi.} (16. g3 {wins a pawn but
weakens the kingside too much.} Qh6 17. Nxe4 fxe4 18. Qxe4 Nc5 19. Qc2 (19. Qg2
Bc8 $5 $15 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 20. b4 Bh3 21. Qh1 Na4 22. Rab1 Qf6 $19 23. f3 Nxb2
24. Rxb2 e4) 19... Bc8 20. Rf1 (20. e4 Rxf2 $1 21. Kxf2 Qxh2+ 22. Ke1 Qxg3+ 23.
Kd2 Qf4+ 24. Ke1 Nxe4 $19) (20. f4 Bf5 21. Qc3 Ne4 22. Qe1 Qg6 $17 {With
lasting kingside pressure.} 23. fxe5 $2 Ng5 $19) 20... Bf5 21. Qd1 Bh3 22. Re1
Rxf2 $1 23. Kxf2 Ne4+ {Mating soon.}) 16... Rf6 17. Nxe4 (17. f4 {does not
slow down Black's initiative.} Nxd2 18. Qxd2 Rh6 19. h3 Re8 20. fxe5 Nxe5 21.
Rxf5 Bc8 22. Rf4 Qg5 $15) 17... fxe4 18. f4 (18. g3 Qh3 19. Qxe4 Nc5 20. Qg2
Qxg2+ 21. Kxg2 Nxb3 22. Rad1 Rf7 $11) 18... exf3 19. Rxf3 Rxf3 20. Bxf3 Rf8 21.
Rf1 Bc8 $11 *

