1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 a5 8.
b3 O-O 9. Be2 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bb2 Qe7 12. b4 {White plays a move which is
part of his main plan in many lines while keeping the rooks' development
flexible. But at this stage, it loses a tempo and weakens c4.} Ne4 13. Qc2 f5
14. Ne1 {The most dangerous idea. White plans f2-f3 followed by Nd3, trying to
increase his area of control.} (14. Nd2 Qg5 {This is the most active answer.} (
14... Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Rf6 {is also playable, though.} 16. f3 Rh6 17. Rf2 Qh4 18.
g3 Rg6 19. Bc3 {Oms Pallisse,J (2476)-Sanchez Botella,L (2139) Andorra 2005 
(1-0, 50). After having weakened the enemy kingside, Black should not go all
in but instead involve as many forces as possible in the attack.} axb4 20. axb4
Rxa1+ 21. Bxa1 h5 22. Qa2 Qd8 23. Qa7 h4 $1 24. Qxb7 hxg3 25. hxg3 Rxg3+ 26.
Rg2 Rh3 27. Bf1 Qh4 28. Qc8+ Nf8 29. Rxg7+ {White is forced to search for a
draw.} Kxg7 30. Qxc7+ Kg6 31. Bxh3 Qxh3 32. Qxd6 Qxf3 $11 {The game will
inadvertedly end in a perpetual.}) 15. d5 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 Nf6 17. f4 Qg6 (17...
Ne4 {is premature.} 18. Qd4 Qg6 19. Bh5 $1 Qf6 20. Qxe4 fxe4 21. Bxf6 Rxf6 22.
dxe6 Rxe6 23. Be2 $14 {The mobile kingside majority ensures White better
chances in the endgame.}) 18. Bf3 Rfe8 $5 $146 {I believe that Black does best
to keep the tension for a while. But in a correspondence chess game he managed
to hold his own even after making concessions.} (18... Ne4 19. Bxe4 fxe4 20.
dxe6 Qxe6 21. c5 dxc5 22. bxc5 Rad8 23. Qf2 bxc5 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. Qb2+ Rf6 26.
Qxb7 $14 {Borkovec,M-Fric,L ICCF email 2009 (1/2-1/2, 45)}) (18... exd5 19.
cxd5 Rfe8 20. Rac1 Re7 21. b5 Rae8 22. Bxf6 Qxf6 23. Rc3 Qf7 24. Rfc1 Ba8 25.
Qd4 Bb7 26. R3c2 {1/2-1/2 Eigenmann,W (1903) -Ziegler,P (2001) ICCF email 2010.
In over-the-board chess White would keep trying for a while at least.}) 19. Bc3
(19. Rfe1 Re7 20. Bd4 h6 $11 {Leaves White short of constructive plans.}) 19...
exd5 {With the bishop exposed on c3, this is well-timed.} 20. Bxf6 (20. cxd5
Ne4 21. Qd3 Qf7 22. Qd4 Qf6 $11) 20... Qxf6 21. b5 c5 22. bxc6 Bxc6 23. Bxd5+
Bxd5 24. Qxd5+ Qe6 $11) (14. Rad1 {offers Black a free tempo to regroup.} Ndf6
$5 15. d5 e5 16. Nd2 Bc8 17. Nxe4 (17. f3 Nxd2 18. Qxd2 Bd7 19. Bc3 axb4 20.
axb4 b5 21. c5 Be8 {, and White may experience problems with his d5-pawn.})
17... fxe4 18. Bc3 axb4 19. axb4 {Barria Zuniga,D (2438)-Dgebuadze,A (2544)
San Sebastian 2011 (1/2-1/2, 29)} Qf7 (19... h5 $5 {, planning ...Bg4.} 20. h3
g5 {, followed by ...g5-g4, with counterplay.}) 20. Ra1 (20. Rd2 Qg6 21. Re1
Bg4 22. Bf1 h5 $11) 20... Rxa1 21. Bxa1 Bg4 22. Bxg4 Nxg4 23. Qxe4 Qh5 24. h3
Nxf2 $1 25. Qc2 Nxh3+ 26. gxh3 Rxf1+ 27. Kxf1 Qxh3+ $11 {Black will soon get
the third pawn for the piece and the bishop will be rather passive.}) 14... c5
$5 $146 {Black immediately blocks the vulnerable pawn.} (14... Qg5 {is
ineffective due to} 15. Qc1 {, followed by f2-f3 and Nd3.}) (14... e5 {allows}
15. c5 {In this line White is a tempo up (b3-b4) with respect to Line 14 below.
}) 15. Nd3 {The most flexible move.} (15. f3 Nef6 16. Nd3 e5 {exposes White to
the threat ...e5-e4.} 17. bxc5 bxc5 18. dxc5 (18. d5 e4 19. fxe4 Qxe4 20. Rf3
Ba6 21. Rc1 Rab8 $11 {This is one of the lines where we can feel that b2-b4
has led to the opening of the queenside to Black's favour.}) (18. Nf2 e4 19. f4
d5 $11 {Black can afford to open the centre, as the white knight is
temporarily passive.}) 18... dxc5 19. Nf2 Ne8 20. Rad1 Nd6 $11 {With a solid
position and a harmonious regrouping for Black.}) 15... b5 $5 {Taking
advantage of the vulnerability of c4 and the active knight on e4.} (15... e5 {
is in fact also playable.} 16. bxc5 bxc5 17. d5 Ba6 {Once again the drawbacks
of b3-b4 are obvious.} 18. f3 Nef6 19. Nf2 a4 {Both attacked pawns are taboo
due to ...Nxd5.} 20. Rfe1 {Threatening Qxa4.} Rab8 21. Rab1 Rb3 $11) 16. dxc5 (
16. cxb5 c4 17. Qxc4 Rfc8 18. Qa2 Nd2 {Due to the threat ...Bd5, trapping the
queen, White is in danger of losing the exchange with normal compensation at
most.} 19. d5 $5 Bxd5 20. Bf6 Bxa2 21. Bxe7 Bc4 22. Rfd1 Ne4 {With adequate
compensation for the pawn due to White's hanging minor pieces.}) 16... bxc4 17.
Qxc4 (17. cxd6 Nxd6 18. Nc5 Bd5 19. f3 axb4 20. axb4 Nxc5 21. bxc5 Nb5 22. Bd4
Qg5 $11) 17... dxc5 18. Nf4 axb4 19. axb4 Nd2 {Play transposes to an ending
with just a symbolic advantage for White.} 20. Qxe6+ Qxe6 21. Nxe6 Nxf1 22.
Nxf8 Rxa1 23. Bxa1 Kxf8 24. Kxf1 cxb4 25. Bb5 Nc5 26. Be5 b3 {[%cal Gb7a6] The
most straightforward way to a draw.} (26... Kf7 27. Bc4+ Kg6 $11 {, followed
by ...Ba6, is also good.}) 27. Bd6+ Kf7 28. Bxc5 b2 29. Bc4+ (29. Bd3 $2 Ba6 $1
$19) 29... Kg6 30. Ba2 Be4 $11 {In the opposite-coloured bishops ending
White's extra pawn will not play any part.} *

