1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 a5 8.
b3 O-O 9. Be2 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bb2 Qe7 12. Rad1 {A straightforward way of
anticipating ...Ne4. The main drawback of this move is that it deviates from
the natural plan involving Rfd1 and Rac1.} Rfd8 {Black switches to the central
plan based on ...d6-d5 and/or ...c7-c5, depending on White's reaction. With
the centre under tension, White will feel that a rook is missing on the left
side of the board. At the same time, Black's rooks are optimally placed. For
the time being, the queen's rook is ready to sustain ...a5-a4 or else to join
its colleague in the centre with ...Rac8.} (12... Ne4 13. Qc2 f5 {runs into}
14. d5 e5 15. Nd2 Nxd2 16. Rxd2 {Making perfect use of the rook.} f4 {This
familiar idea, preventing f2-f4, allows White to prove his superior
development.} 17. exf4 Rxf4 {Kulaots,K (2574)-Amin,B (2665) Al Ain 2015 (1/2-1/
2, 31)} (17... exf4 18. Bd3 Qh4 19. Re2 $16) 18. g3 Rf7 19. Bd3 {, followed by
f2-f4 soon.}) 13. Qc2 {Taking the queen out of the knight's range.} (13. Qc3 {
prepares to meet ...c7-c5 with d4-d5, as g7 would be under indirect pressure,
but exposes the queen to} d5 14. cxd5 ({The attempt to restore the optimal
coordination with} 14. Rc1 {wastes a tempo.} c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Nd2 Rac8 {
, and White is hanging a bit.}) 14... Nxd5 15. Qc2 c5 16. Bc4 (16. dxc5 Rac8 $5
{leaves White's queenside vulnerable.} 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 bxc5 19. b5 c4 $11)
16... N5f6 {Preparing ...Be4 or ...Bd5.} 17. Qe2 (17. dxc5 Qxc5 $1 (17... Nxc5
{allows White to exchange all rooks, thus correcting his initial lack of
coordination.} 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Rd1 $14 {, with better chances due to the
two bishops.}) 18. Qe2 Qe7 19. Nd4 Rac8 {Black is perfectly developed and
White cannot enjoy his two bishops, as the one on c4 is exposed. Here is a
correspondence game that ended in a draw.} 20. f3 Ne5 21. Bb5 Nd5 22. Rc1 Nc7
23. Ba4 Ba6 24. Rxc7 Bxe2 25. Rxe7 Bxf1 26. Kxf1 Nd3 {The bishop is in trouble
and Black retrieves the material} 27. Nc6 Nxb2 28. Nxd8 Rxd8 29. Rd7 Rxd7 30.
Bxd7 {1/2-1/2 Vegjeleki,A (2295)-Suninen,J (2304) ICCF email 2014}) 17... Ne4 {
[%cal Ge4d6]} (17... a4 $6 {is premature.} 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. bxa4 Rxa4 20. Bb5
Ra5 21. a4 Bd5 22. Nd2 $14 {Roiz,M (2651)-Kortschnoj,V (2567) Porto Carras
2011 (1/2-1/2, 52)}) 18. Ne5 cxd4 19. Nxd7 Rxd7 20. Rxd4 Rxd4 21. Bxd4 e5 {
Black is in time to neutralize White's pressure on the dark squares.} 22. Bb2 (
22. Bxb6 $2 Qd6 23. Qf3 Qxb6 24. Qxf7+ Kh8 $17) 22... Nd6 23. Bd3 e4 $5 (23...
Qe6 24. Rd1 f6 $11) 24. Bc2 Ba6 25. Qg4 f5 26. Qd1 Rd8 27. Qd5+ Nf7 28. Qxf5
Bxf1 29. Kxf1 $44 {With just normal compensation for White.}) (13. b4 $146 {
does not look too logical after the rook has left the a-file.} axb4 14. axb4 b5
$5 {A familiar plan.} (14... c5 {is also playable.}) 15. c5 (15. cxb5 Nb6 16.
Ra1 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 d5 $11 {, followed by the f6-knight's transfer to d6.}) 15...
dxc5 16. bxc5 Bd5 {A promising pawn sacrifice, yielding Black a long-term
queenside initiative.} 17. Bxb5 Rdb8 18. Bd3 Ne4 19. Qc1 Ra2 20. Ba1 Rba8 21.
Bb2 Rb8 22. Ba3 $5 f5 23. Nd2 Nf8 $5 {Planning ...Ng6. It is not easy to
indicate an effective freeing plan for White.} 24. f3 Qg5 $1 25. fxe4 (25. Rfe1
