1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 a5 8.
b3 O-O 9. Be2 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bb2 Qe7 12. Qc3 {This was played only once
in the concrete tabiya after move 11, but it is worth examining in some detail,
as it transposes to a specific line of the 4.Qc2 Nimzo-Indian. White prepares
to meet ...c7-c5 with d4-d5 while maintaining the possibility of placing his
rooks on d1 and c1, should Black play ...d6-d5. If we compare this to the most
active Nimzo lines of this kind, Black has invested some time into ...a7-a5
and ...Qe7, but both are useful in principle. Since White could not play b2-b4,
the c5-square will be available after d4-d5, while the queen can sustain ...
e6-e5, should the knight retreat from f3.} Ne4 13. Qc2 f5 14. Ne1 {The most
ambitious approach.} (14. Rad1 {allows Black to activate his rook with} Rf6 15.
d5 Rh6 16. g3 (16. b4 c5 17. bxa5 Rxa5 18. dxe6 Qxe6 {, left Black with a
compact structure and active play.} 19. Rd3 Ra8 20. Rfd1 Qg6 21. Ba1 Re8 22.
Qa4 Re7 23. Qa7 Bc6 24. Qc7 Ba4 25. Re1 Qe8 $17 {Zhou,J (2600)-Abdulla,A (2473)
Al Ain 2015 (1/2-1/2, 63)}) 16... c5 17. Ne1 Ng5 {With promising kingside play.
} 18. Nf3 {A bit strange, but Black could answer in the same way as below
against other moves, too.} Nh3+ 19. Kg2 {Nenciulescu,S (2059)-Dehaybe, A (2129)
LSS email 2012 (1/2-1/2, 26)} Rf8 $11) (14. b4 {leads to similar play:} Rf6 15.
c5 (15. d5 Rh6 16. g3 Rf8 17. Rab1 {De Carlos Arregui,I (2392) -Asturiano
Molina,J (2429) ICCF email 2009 (1/2-1/2, 27)} e5 $5 $146 18. bxa5 Bc8 19. axb6
Nxb6 20. a4 Nd7 21. Nd2 Ndc5 22. Rbe1 Rff6 {, with excellent play for the pawn.
}) 15... Bd5 16. cxd6 cxd6 17. Bb5 {Schindler,S (2296)-Bolz,J (2157) ICCF
email 2011 (1/2-1/2, 49)} Rh6 $1 $146 {Black can burn the bridges behind
himself.} 18. Qc7 Ng5 19. Nxg5 (19. Ne1 $2 Nh3+ 20. Kh1 Qh4 21. Qxd6 f4 {
mates soon.}) 19... Qxg5 20. e4 Qf4 21. h3 Qxe4 (21... Rg6 22. exd5 Qf3 23. g3
Rxg3+ {draws}) 22. f3 Qe3+ 23. Rf2 Nf6 {, and Black should not be worse.}) (14.
Nd2 Qg5 15. f4 (15. g3 Qh6) 15... Qg6 $11) (14. d5 e5 15. Nd2 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 e4
$5 {Planning ...Ne5, ...Rae8, ...Bc8 and later ...f5-f4.} (16... Nc5 17. Qc2 {
Korchmar,V (2432)-Kryakvin,D (2610) St Petersburg 2019 (1/2-1/2, 23)} c6 18. b4
Nd7 19. dxc6 Bxc6 {is also possible.}) 17. f4 exf3 18. gxf3 Rae8 19. Bd4 c5 20.
dxc6 Bxc6 $11 {Due to the mutual weaknesses, the game is balanced.}) 14... e5
$1 {The best reaction under the given circumstances, justifying the queen's
presence on e7.} (14... Qg5 15. Qc1 Rf6 {, as for instance in Van Wely,L (2683)
-Ivanchuk,V (2750) Monte Carlo 2007 (0-1, 27)} 16. c5 $1 $16 {The point is
that after} (16. f3 $6 Qh5 {is fine for Black}) 16... Bd5 $2 17. f3 {wins a
piece:} Qh5 18. fxe4 Qxe2 19. exd5 $18) 15. Nd3 Nef6 16. dxe5 (16. Rac1 c5 {
stabilizes the centre, with comfortable black play.} 17. Rcd1 (17. d5 b5 $1 {
, threatening to undermine the queenside with ...a5-a4.} 18. a4 bxa4 19. bxa4
Ba6 $11 {, with adequate counterplay.}) 17... cxd4 18. exd4 e4 19. Nf4 g5 20.
Nh3 h6 21. Rde1 {Kameneckas,K (2427)-Santos Crespo,I (2448) ICCF email 2008 
(0-1, 40)} d5 22. f3 Rac8 {, with excellent play.}) 16... dxe5 17. c5 {The
only active try.} bxc5 18. Rac1 Ba6 19. Rfe1 Rfb8 $1 $146 {After this move it
appears that White's queenside is not that solid either.} (19... c4 $6 20. bxc4
c5 21. f4 $16 {Gurevich,M (2644)-Bologan,V (2669) Sanxenxo 2004 (0-1, 66)}) 20.
Bf1 (20. Nxc5 Nxc5 21. Qxc5 Qxc5 22. Rxc5 Rxb3 23. Rxa5 Rxb2 24. Rxa6 Rxa6 25.
Bxa6 Kf8 $11) 20... Rb6 21. Ba1 (21. Nxc5 Nxc5 22. Qxc5 Qxc5 23. Rxc5 Bxf1 24.
Kxf1 Rxb3 25. Bxe5 Nd7 26. Rd5 Nb6 {If Black avoids the move repetition, the
