1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. e3 {The last four lines in this
database are dedicated to the systems without an early a2-a3. Since the bishop
risks being left out of play on b4 and taking on d2 without being attacked
basically wastes a tempo, Black needs to switch to different structures.} Bb7
6. Bd3 {The most active bishop's development, creating the threat e3-e4 after
castling.} (6. Be2 {offers Black a wider choice.} O-O 7. O-O d5 ({Switching to
a Hedgehog structure is also possible:} 7... Be7 $5 8. b3 c5 9. Bb2 d6 {
Black has lost a tempo, but White does not have anything better than doing the
same with} 10. Bd3 {now or in the near future, transposing to a peaceful but
complex 4.e3 Queen's Indian line.} Nbd7 {, and so on.}) 8. a3 Be7 9. b4 c5 10.
bxc5 bxc5 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. cxd5 (12. Qb3 Ba6 {leaves the c4-pawn pinned.}) 12...
Bxd5 {This is comfortable because e3-e4 is not a threat yet.} 13. Qc2 {
Williams,S (2487)-Morrison,G (2328) Sunningdale 2007 (1-0, 29)} Rc8 14. e4 Bb7
15. Bb2 cxd4 16. Qxc7 Rxc7 17. Rfc1 Nc6 {The game is even, as the following
lines prove:} 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Rxc7 Nxe2+ 20. Kf1 (20. Kh1 $2 Nxe4 {threatens
mate in one.} 21. Nxe4 Bxe4 22. Re1 Bd8 $1 23. Rc4 Bd3 $19) 20... Ba6 21. Bxf6
Nf4+ $1 (21... Bxf6 $2 22. Rxa7 $1 $18 Rd8 23. Rxa6 Rxd2 24. Rb8+ Bd8 25. Raa8)
22. Kg1 Ne2+ 23. Kh1 {The only way to avoid an immediate draw, but White will
have potential back rank problems now.} Bxf6 24. Rxa7 Rd8 25. Rxa6 Rxd2 26.
Rb8+ Bd8 27. g3 Kf8 $11) 6... O-O 7. O-O d5 {The simplest. Black is heading
for symmetry in the centre, based on the fact that the white queen's knight is
not on the most active square c3.} 8. a3 ({Delaying a2-a3 offers Black the
possibility of later retreating with his bishop to d6.} 8. b3 Nbd7 9. Bb2 Ne4
10. Rc1 f5 11. a3 Bd6 12. b4 {Kostic,V (2335)-Duer,A (2390) Austria 1989 (1/
2-1/2, 23)} Nxd2 13. Nxd2 (13. Qxd2 $2 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxf3 15. Bxe6+ Kh8 16.
gxf3 Qg5+ 17. Kh1 Qh5 18. f4 Qf3+ 19. Kg1 Rf6 $19) 13... dxc4 14. Nxc4 Bxh2+
15. Kxh2 Qh4+ 16. Kg1 Bxg2 {Lasker's combination against Bauer, but leading
only to a draw in this case.} 17. f3 Rf6 18. Rc2 Bh3 19. Rff2 Rg6+ 20. Rg2 Bxg2
21. Rxg2 Rxg2+ 22. Kxg2 Qg5+ 23. Kf2 Qh4+ 24. Ke2 Qh2+ 25. Ke1 b5 26. Nd2 (26.
Ne5 Nxe5 27. dxe5 Qxb2 $19) 26... Qg3+ {, with a perpetual.}) 8... Be7 (8...
Bd6 {is less accurate now, as after} 9. b4 c5 10. cxd5 $14 {Black does not
have ... Qxd5.} exd5 (10... Bxd5 11. e4 {endangers Black's minor pieces. The
only move is} c4 $16 {, which loses a pawn to} 12. exd5 cxd3 13. dxe6 fxe6 14.
Qb3 $16) (10... Nxd5 11. dxc5 bxc5 12. bxc5 Bxc5 13. Qc2 Nf6 14. Bb2 Nbd7 15.
Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Bxh7+ Nxh7 17. Qxc5 $16) 11. bxc5 bxc5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 $14) 9. b4 {
White is hoping for some light initiative, but Black should have little
trouble neutralising it.} (9. cxd5 exd5 10. b4 {Turns the position too static
to be dangerous for Black.} Nbd7 11. Bb2 Bd6 12. b5 (12. Ne5 Qe7 13. Ndf3 Ne4
14. Qc2 f6 15. Nc6 Qe6 16. b5 {Khalifman,A (2645)-Rozentalis,E (2600) Rakvere
1993 (1/2-1/2, 43)} a6 17. a4 Nb8 18. g3 Nxc6 19. bxc6 Bc8 20. Ne1 Qe8 21. f3
Ng5 {White does not have any queenside play, while Black is not without
chances on the kingside.}) 12... Qe7 13. a4 a6 14. Qb3 axb5 15. axb5 Ne4 16.
Rfc1 Ndf6 17. Nf1 Ng4 18. Rc2 Rxa1 19. Bxa1 Ra8 20. Bb2 Ng5 21. Ne1 Nf6 22. Be2
h5 $11 {Once again, Black has the more promising side of an equal position,
