1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3 {The other main system without
an early a2-a3. Since 4.g3 is more ambitious than 4.e3 in the Queen's Indian,
the same partly applies here.} Bb7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d5 {The same reaction as
recommended against 5.e3.} ({For Hedgehog specialists,} 7... Be7 {may be
appealing. too.} 8. Qc2 {The most active move, preparing e2-e4.} (8. b3 c5 9.
Bb2 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qc7 12. e4 d6 {leads to an English Hedgehog,
where the knight is not especially well placed on d2, justifying the tempo
wasted by the black bishop.}) 8... c5 9. e4 d5 (9... cxd4 $2 {runs into} 10. e5
Ng4 11. h3 Nh6 12. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 13. Bxb7 $16) 10. cxd5 exd5 11. e5 {The only
way to keep some life in the position.} Nfd7 12. Re1 Nc6 13. a3 Rc8 $11 {
, with chances for both sides.}) 8. a3 (8. cxd5 {, transposing to a Queen's
Indian hanging pawns structure, is examined in Line 18.}) 8... Be7 9. b4 (9.
cxd5 exd5 10. b4 {is once again more static (see Line 15).} a5 11. b5 c6 12.
bxc6 Nxc6 {Since the bishop has left the f1-a6 diagonal, Black's queenside is
not that easy to block, despite its apparent lack of mobility.} 13. Bb2 (13. e3
b5 14. Ne5 Bd6 15. Bb2 a4 16. Qb1 Rb8 17. Bc3 Ba8 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Nf3 Qe7 20.
Ne5 Rfc8 21. Bh3 Bd7 22. Nxd7 Nxd7 23. Qb2 Rc6 24. Rfc1 h5 $11 {Wei,Y (2728)
-Yu,Y (2749) Beijing 2017 (1/2-1/2, 69) Due to the potenatially dangerous
queenside majority, Black is not worse.}) 13... b5 (13... a4 $5 14. Ne5 {
Fedoseev,V (2718)-Riazantsev,A (2650) St Petersburg 2017 (1-0, 57)} b5 $11) 14.
e3 a4 15. Qb1 Qb6 16. Rc1 Rfc8 17. Ne5 h6 {At this height, this is just a loss
of time.} (17... Bd6 $5 18. Nd3 Na5 19. Bc3 Rab8 20. Bb4 Rxc1+ 21. Qxc1 Bxb4
22. Nxb4 Rc8 23. Qe1 Nc4 24. Nb1 Qd6 $11) 18. Bc3 Rc7 19. Qb2 Rac8 20. Bf1 Ba6
21. Nxc6 $6 (21. Nd3 $5 {offers chances to maintain control due to the tempo
wasted by Black.}) 21... Rxc6 22. Nf3 Ne4 23. Bb4 Bxb4 24. axb4 {So,W (2780)
-Vidit,S (2718) chess.com INT 2018 (1-0, 48)} Rxc1 $1 25. Rxc1 Rxc1 26. Qxc1
Qf6 27. Kg2 Qf5 $17 {White has serious worries on both wings.}) 9... a5 ({
Black can also try to play on the light squares:} 9... dxc4 $5 10. Nxc4 Bd5 11.
Ne3 (11. Qc2 c5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. b5 a6 14. bxa6 Nc6 15. Bb2 Rxa6 16. Ne3 Bxf3
17. exf3 Nd4 18. Qc4 Qa8 19. f4 Qa7 20. a4 Rb8 21. Bc3 Ne8 22. a5 Nd6 23. Qa2
N6b5 24. Be1 Nc6 25. Nc4 Nb4 26. Qa4 Bf6 $11) 11... Be4 12. Bb2 a5 13. b5 c6
14. bxc6 Nxc6 $11) 10. b5 c5 {The position remains interesting, but as the
games below show, chances are about equal.} 11. Bb2 (11. bxc6 Nxc6 {Speeds up
Black's development and leaves him with a mobile queenside majority.} 12. Rb1
Ba6 13. cxd5 (13. Qb3 Rb8 14. Bb2 dxc4 15. Nxc4 {Valgmae,T (2226)-Petursson,M 
(2520) Puhajarve 2015 (0-1, 72)} b5 16. Nce5 a4 $11) 13... exd5 14. Re1 b5 15.
Bb2 Rc8 16. Bh3 Rc7 17. Rc1 {Kelires,A (2505)-Gevorgyan,M (2256) Paleochora
2017 (1/2-1/2, 40)} Bc8 18. Bxc8 (18. Bg2 b4 $11 19. Qb3 Be6) 18... Qxc8 $11
19. e4 $6 b4 20. e5 Ne4 21. axb4 (21. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 22. Rxe4 bxa3 23. Ba1 Nxd4
$19) 21... Bxb4 22. Re3 Nxd2 23. Nxd2 Ne7 $15) 11... Nbd7 12. e3 (12. Ne5 Rc8
13. e3 {Alekhine,A-Colle,E Scarborough/ North Yorkshire 1926 (1-0, 36)} cxd4
14. exd4 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Qe2 Qc7 18. Rfc1 {Keeping a3
defended.} (18. Rac1 Rfd8 19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Rd2 {retrieves the pawn.})
18... Rfd8 19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Qd7 21. Rc2 Bc5 22. a4 Qd3 $11 {With enough
compensation for the pawn due to the more active pieces.}) (12. Rc1 Ne4 {
Not the only plan, of course.} 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Nd2 f5 (14... cxd4 15. Nxe4 f5
16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bc6 Nc5 {is also comfortable for Black due to
his outpost on c5.}) 15. e3 cxd4 16. exd4 {Pavlovic,M (2457)-Lajthajm,B (2518)
Belgrade 2008 (1/2-1/2, 24)} Rc8 17. Qe2 Bg5 18. Rfd1 Qe7 19. Rc2 Rfd8 20. Nf1
a4 21. Ne3 g6 $11 {Both sides are well regrouped and the position remains in a
static equilibrium.}) 12... Rc8 13. Qe2 Rc7 14. Rfc1 Qa8 15. Ne5 cxd4 16. Bxd4
Rfc8 17. a4 Bb4 $11 18. Nc6 $2 {Just throwing away a pawn.} Bxc6 19. bxc6 Rxc6
20. Qd1 Bxd2 21. Qxd2 Rxc4 $17 {Malakhatko,V (2539)-Sargissian,G (2671) Minsk
2014 (0-1, 101)} *

