1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6 5. g3 Bb7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O d5 8.
cxd5 {Transposing to a genuine Queen's Indian.} ({Delaying the exchange does
not offer White much:} 8. Ne5 Re8 9. a3 Bf8 10. b4 Nbd7 11. Ndf3 {Li,C (2751)
-Sargissian,G (2702) Huaian 2016 (0-1, 101)} dxc4 $5 12. Nxc4 Bd5 13. Qd3 c5
$11) 8... exd5 {Black will have to waste a tempo by willingly retreating with
the bishop. But White's queen's knight is not on c3, which is the best square
in this structure. Similar positions arise from the 4.g3 Ba6 5.Nbd2 Queen's
Indian, when Black can play ...Bb7 and ...d7-d5 after castling. If Black plays
...Be7 in our line, the transposition will be perfect, but in many lines he
can do even better with ...Re8 and ...Bf8.} 9. Ne5 {The most popular move,
increasing the pressure in the centre at once.} (9. Qc2 Re8 {does not make
much of a difference, since Ne5 is part of White's plan anyway.}) (9. Qb3 $5 {
seems to be the latest fashion at high level. White's main idea is to improve
the knight's placement with Nb1-c3 and keep the b-pawn pinned, so that Black
cannot play ...c7-c5, dxc5 ...bxc5.} Nc6 $5 {An interesting way to take
advantage of the queen's exposure.} ({In fact, the simplest continuation is} 
9... Be7 10. Nb1 {Firouzja,A (2607)-Yu,Y (2764) St Petersburg 2018 (1/2-1/2,
131)} Na6 11. Nc3 c5 {, reaching a normal position with an extra tempo for
Black. While ...c5-c4 should not be underestimated, Black would probably
continue with ...Ne4 and ...Bf6. As for the main idea behind Qb3, if} 12. dxc5
Nxc5 13. Qc2 Rc8 {, Black is two tempi ahead of the corresponding Queen's
Indian lines.}) (9... Bd6 {, followed by ...a7-a6, without the intention of a
later c7-c5, is the most popular plan. A bit passive and unconvincing. It may
be that modern players have forgotten how to play with the hanging/isolated
pawns against the fianchetto.}) 10. Ne5 (10. Nb1 Re8 11. a3 Bf8 12. Nc3 Na5 13.
Qc2 Ne4 14. Bf4 c5 15. dxc5 Bxc5 {offers Black active piece play. The knight
is well placed on a5 as it targets the weak c4 and b3 squares. And if} 16. b4
Rc8 $1 {, White is in trouble already.} 17. bxc5 Rxc5 18. Bd2 d4) (10. a3 Bd6 {
Planning ...a5-a4 followed by ...Na5. And if a3-a4, the knight gladly jumps to
b4.} 11. Nb1 {, following the initial plan and preparing to prevent ...a5-a4.}
Na5 12. Qc2 c5 $11 13. dxc5 $6 bxc5 $15) 10... Bd6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Qc2 Bb5
13. Nb1 Bd7 14. Nc3 c6 15. a4 a5 {Black has secured the queenside and
activated the light-squared bishop. He has chances of making the kingside his
attacking territory.} 16. b3 Re8 17. Ba3 $6 (17. e4 $1 $11) 17... Bb4 18. Bxb4
axb4 19. Nd1 Ne4 (19... h5 $5 $15 {is simpler.}) 20. f3 Ng5 21. Qd2 Qe7 22. Re1
Ne6 {A great square for the knight with hanging pawns on the board.} 23. Nf2 c5
24. e3 c4 $15 {Janik,I (2454) -Petrosyan,M (2564) Skopje 2019 (0-1, 50)}) 9...
Re8 10. Ndf3 (10. a3 Bf8 11. b4 a5 {leads to a familiar scenario.} 12. b5 c6
13. bxc6 Nxc6 $11) 10... Ne4 11. Bf4 Bf8 12. Rc1 (12. Qc2 c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14.
Rfd1 Qc8 15. Nd3 Na6 $15 {Black has very active play.} 16. Ng5 c4 $1 17. Nc1
Nb4 18. Qb1 h6 19. Nxe4 (19. Nf3 Bc5 20. Nd4 Nxf2 21. Kxf2 g5 22. Be3 Rxe3 23.
Kxe3 Qe6+ 24. Kf2 Bxd4+ 25. Rxd4 Qf6+ {wins}) 19... dxe4 20. a3 Nd5 21. Na2
Nxf4 22. gxf4 e3 $19 {Paunovic, D (2430) -Polugaevsky,L (2590)/Belgrade 1988/
TD (0-1, 28)}) 12... c5 13. Nd2 {Raetsky,A (2420)-Makarov,M (2515) Sochi 2007 
(1/2-1/2, 18)} (13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Nd2 Nf6 15. Nd3 Nbd7 16. Bg5 Qb6 17. Bxf6
Nxf6 18. Nb1 {Kozul,Z (2490)-Bareev,E (2555)/ Ljubljana/Portoroz 1989 (1/2, 27)
. Once the knight has gone far from the centre,} c4 $5 $17 {offers Black
chances to take over the initiative.}) 13... Na6 14. dxc5 Naxc5 $11 {Black is
much better coordinated, which compensates for the relative weakness of the
isolani.} *

